<HEAD>Psychiatrist Report on Nussbaum Details Lisa's Last Night</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout with confidential psychiatric report on Nussbaum;
No pickup. Note contents.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The night before <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>'s adoptive 6-year-old daughter was removed unconscious from their apartment, his live-in companion said she heard noises in a bedroom `` like <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> throwing <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON>,'' sources said Monday. <PERSON> Hedda </PERSON> <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> told a psychiatrist at <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Presbyterian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> on Nov. 20 that <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>, who is accused of beating <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> to death, then handed the child to her, saying, `` This is your child; what have you done; this has gone far enough,'' <ORGANIZATION> WCBS-TV </ORGANIZATION> said Monday, quoting from a copy of the unidentified psychiatrist's report. The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> confirmed the contents of the report through sources close to the case. <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> told the psychiatrist that <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> was angry that night because <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> refused to drink water after he had given her and <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> hot pepper. She said he gave them the hot pepper to get them to drink more water. She later heard noises from the bedroom that sounded `` like <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> throwing <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON>,'' the report said. Afterward, <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> gave the child to <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON>, who placed her on the floor and noticed water and food coming out of her mouth. The report said that <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> thought <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> may have poured water down <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON>'s mouth and that she was drowning. <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> said she then began pumping the child's chest. <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> told the psychiatrist that <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> had left the apartment shortly afterward and returned about 10 p.m.. At about 6 a.m. <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> said, `` She's stopped breathing'' and told <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> to `` call 911. <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON>, 46, a former editor of children's books, also was charged with <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON>'s murder, but the charges against her later were dropped. She has spent the last year undergoing physical and psychiatric rehabilitation for injuries the prosecution says she suffered at <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>'s hands. At <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>'s trial on Monday a photographer testified that he used poses and lighting tricks to hide bruises he saw on the battered child when he took pictures of her in school two weeks before she was found dead. <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON> <PERSON> Gross </PERSON>, working that day for <ORGANIZATION> Scholastic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Books </ORGANIZATION>, said he initially was reluctant to photograph the first-grader when he visited her school on Oct. 22, 1987, because of her numerous bruises and her unkempt appearance. `` I observed some bruises underneath her left eye, by the cheeks, a bump on the forehead and underneath the chin here, a bruise, and some bruises on her arms,'' <PERSON> Gross </PERSON> said. `` The hair was very unkempt ... uneven,'' and her clothes were `` very rumpled, dirty,'' he said. <PERSON> Gross </PERSON> said he eventually took several black and white pictures of <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON>. He said he was drawn to her when she began directing two other children on posing the way he wanted them. `` She seemed older, more mature,'' he said. `` I put her on the right side and I flooded my light into her and I had her turn her head this way and down so you would n't see it. The last thing my client wants to see is bruises,'' <PERSON> Gross </PERSON> said. He said the rumpled and dirty quality of <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON>'s clothing also was eliminated `` in the way I photographed them.'' <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>, 47, is charged with murder for allegedly beating <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> to death. The disbarred lawyer denies that he hit the child. He says she fell unconscious after choking on food she had vomited. <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> was taken unconscious from <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> Greenwich </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Village </LOCATION> apartment early on Nov. 2, 1987, and died three days later at a hospital. Prosecutors are trying to show by Gross' photographs and testimony that <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> was an abused child in the weeks before her death. They hope to eliminate any reasonable inference except that the abuse was inflicted by <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>, who illegally adopted the girl.
