<HEAD>South Korea's Roh Indicates He May Pardon Chun, Who Prepares
Apology</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> <PERSON> Tae-woo </PERSON> was quoted as saying Monday that he wants to resolve politically the controversy raging over his predecessor, <PERSON> Chun </PERSON> <PERSON> Doo-hwan </PERSON>, an indication he may pardon <PERSON> Chun </PERSON>. <PERSON> Chun </PERSON> is preparing to apologize for corruption and other misdeeds before moving into rural exile. <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> said his government hopes to resolve the controversy over <PERSON> Chun </PERSON> by the end of this year. The former president is being forced out of the capital, <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>, by militant students who rioted and tried to break into his home, demanding that he be arrested and punished for alleged corruption and other abuses during seven years of authoritarian rule. <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> was quoted as saying in an interview with the national daily <ORGANIZATION> Shinmun </ORGANIZATION>, a pro-government newspaper published in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>: `` In handling past wrongdoings, a clear distinction must be made between those -LRB- wrongdoings -RRB- to be dealt with judicially and those to be dealt with politically ... Any wrongdoings by <PERSON> Chun </PERSON> as chief executive of the country should be dealt with politically and there should not be political reprisal against the former chief executive ... `` I will take actions under the principle that any wrongdoings by a chief executive should be dealt with politically and that any political reprisal would only hurt democratic development.'' He made the remarks as the 56-year-old <PERSON> Chun </PERSON> reportedly was preparing to make a nationally televised apology Wednesday. Newspapers said <PERSON> Chun </PERSON> also is to turn over most of his wealth to the government and accept rural exile, a traditional way of repentance for a disgraced Korean. <PERSON> Chun </PERSON> originally planned to leave <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> on Tuesday, but was delayed because of difficulty finding him a safe rural home, news reports said. The former president, who stepped down in February, denies personal wrongdoing. However, about a dozen of his relatives and associates were convicted or charged with corruption involving millions of dollars in public funds. <PERSON> Chun </PERSON> needs a refuge from attack. Some reports said he would go to a mountainside Buddhist temple near an army unit in the north. Others said he might move to central <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. He reportedly is unwelcome in his southern hometown. National Assembly hearings Monday on abuses under the Chun government focused on attempts to stifle press freedom. More than 700 journalists were fired under government pressure and many newspapers and broadcast operations were merged and placed under state control by <PERSON> Chun </PERSON>'s administration. In recent weeks, <PERSON> Chun </PERSON> has been a virtual prisoner in his luxurious <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> home, guarded by hundreds of riot police to prevent attacks by dissidents. <PERSON> Roh </PERSON>'s government has been accused of trying to protect <PERSON> Chun </PERSON> and is trying to defuse public anger without being implicated in the furor. <PERSON> Chun </PERSON>, a former army general, took power with military backing in 1980. He was succeeded by <PERSON> Roh </PERSON>, another former general and close associate, after presidential elections last December.
