<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ten-year-old <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON> does n't care that experts are having trouble explaining how his helium-filled balloon flew 2,500 miles from <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>. He just thinks it's neat, said his mother, <PERSON> Liz </PERSON>. <PERSON> Marc </PERSON>'s 11-inch, yellow balloon was one of 250 launched Oct. 23 to commemorate a local church's anniversary. Each balloon was tied with a string that carried a card asking the finder to return it to the church. The church received 10 to 15 responses, mostly from within 20 miles. <PERSON> Marc </PERSON>'s balloon wound up deflated in the swimming pool of a <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> sheriff's deputy Oct. 30. `` I ca n't explain how it got there,'' Deputy <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> wrote to <PERSON> Marc </PERSON>. `` At that distance, I ca n't believe it was the wind itself. It had to have some help somewhere along the line.'' The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> ca n't explain the trip, either. `` That would be some trick,'' said the weather service's <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Kalembkiewicz </PERSON>. If the balloon were only windblown, it would be `` a once in a lifetime happening.''
