<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JELLICO, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Deciding that it's never too late to change, the mayor wants to give women here the right to vote. Actually, women in this east <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> town of 2,800 have been voting since 1920, when the 19th Amendment to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Constitution was ratified. But the town's 1902 charter still forbids it, and Mayor <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Leach </PERSON> says it's time to have it changed. `` I'd like to see them try to stop the women in <LOCATION> Jellico </LOCATION> from voting,'' said <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON>, wife of City Councilman <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON>. `` They would have a riot on their hands.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 There is such a thing as a free lunch _ just ask about 1,000 people who patronized a downtown restaurant. <PERSON> Jamie </PERSON> <PERSON> Petrolias </PERSON>, owner of <PERSON> Jamie </PERSON>'s on the Square, gave away free chicken and cole slaw lunches Monday to promote his 2-week-old eatery. `` We're just thrilled with the people who came out,'' <PERSON> Petrolias </PERSON> said. The 25-year-old restaurateur, whose family has owned another downtown restaurant for 55 years, said the crowd consumed 1,500 pounds of chicken, 150 pounds of cabbage and 15 gallons of salad oil. He estimated the giveaway cost him about $ 1,500, but added, `` I really have n't figured it out myself. I'm afraid to.'' <PERSON> Petrolias </PERSON> said he was pleased with the crowd, which was orderly and friendly. `` We were just delighted,'' he said `` Our kitchen is n't gigantic, and it was tough to keep up, but we managed.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> <PERSON> Gettel </PERSON> has designed papier-mache heads of the famous for <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>'s Thanksgiving Day parade for 45 years, but to his surprise, parade organizers have had him immortalized. Organizers last week unveiled a 15-pound, baldheaded bust of <PERSON> Gettel </PERSON>. `` They kept it a secret from me for eight months,'' said <PERSON> Gettel </PERSON>, who has designed likenesses ranging from <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON> to <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> <PERSON> Mouse </PERSON> as decorations for parade floats. `` It was packed in the same huge crate as -LRB- civil rights pioneer -RRB- <PERSON> Rosa </PERSON> <PERSON> Parks </PERSON>' head. `` When I pulled it out, I almost flipped. I was so flabbergasted I got all red in the face. Now I'm immortalized. Even when I die I'll be part of the parade.'' This year, nine new heads will make their parade debut, including likenesses of aviator <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Lindbergh </PERSON> and rock singer <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Seger </PERSON>, <PERSON> Gettel </PERSON> said. The heads have become a major attraction at the Thanksgiving procession, where children and adults make a game out of guessing the identities of the lesser-known noggins. `` I just love it so much I can hardly call it a job,'' <PERSON> Gettel </PERSON> said. `` To me, Thanksgiving lasts all year.''
