<HEAD>Biggest Annual Increase Since 1950 Recorded</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANBERRA, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The country's population grew by 268,600 in the past year to total 16.5 million, its biggest annual increase since 1950, the <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION> said. The year that ended June 30 was also just the third since 1950 in which net migration exceeded natural increase _ the excess of births over deaths _ in total population growth, the bureau said Monday. The <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION> said net migration _ permanent arrivals minus departures _ totalled 143,200, also the largest increase since 1949-1950. It said <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> were the largest source of migrants, followed by the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Malayasia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>. Aborigines, the country's indigenous inhabitants, number some 160,000, or about 1 percent of <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>'s population.
