<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 North Korean clams have been imported to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, the first product to arrive since the <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> government approved a policy allowing direct trade with <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. A customs spokesman said today that 40 pounds of short-necked clams from <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> had cleared customs at the port city of <LOCATION> Pusan </LOCATION>. Half the shipment was frozen and half were dried, the spokesman said. The clams were brought to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> by way of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> by <ORGANIZATION> Hyundai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a general trading company, as food samples in preparation for expansion of trading with the north. The <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> government approved the resumption of direct trade of all but military goods in October as a gesture of goodwill in efforts to ease tension and improve relations between the two Koreas. Goods from the communist north had been banned since the division of the peninsula after World War II.
