<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rep. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON>, indicted in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> on conspiracy charges in the <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> corruption scandal, is the 18th person in the last decade to be indicted on criminal charges while serving in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. He is also the second Democratic congressman from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> to be indicted for allegedly using his influence on behalf of the <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a minority-owned <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> machine shop that won no-bid <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> contracts. It has since gone bankrupt. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON>, whose former congressional district in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Bronx </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Borough </LOCATION> abuts <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON>'s, was convicted Aug. 5 of racketeering, mail fraud and accepting bribes from <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> in exchange for his <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> influence <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON>, 71, resigned his <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> seat Aug. 6 after serving nearly 10 terms. He was sentenced Friday to eight years in prison and a $ 242,000 fine. <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON> also was convicted in November 1987 of accepting an illegal gratuity _ a paid vacation _ for helping an ailing shipyard in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Borough </LOCATION>. He was sentenced to 2 -LCB- years in prison and a $ 500,000 fine in that case. <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON> is slated to report to prison authorities on Jan. 9. Last month, former two-term Rep. <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON>, R-Ga., was indicted on perjury charges <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON>, who narrowly lost his seat Nov. 8 as a result of the charges, allegedly lied to a grand jury investigating a proposed $ 850,000 home mortgage loan he discussed with an <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> businessman and an undercover agent posing as a financier. <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> allegedly denied being told the source of the loan could be illicit drug money. <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON>'s trial began last month but was postponed after a juror received a mailing from his campaign. Also last month, Fofo I.F. <PERSON> Sunia </PERSON>, <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Samoa </LOCATION>'s former delegate to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, was sentenced to five to 15 months in prison for participating in a payroll-padding scheme that reportedly earned him $ 39,000. <PERSON> Sunia </PERSON>, a Democrat who had served almost four terms, pleaded guilty to conspiring with his chief aide to defraud the government of $ 130,920 through false payroll claims. The 51-year-old <PERSON> Sunia </PERSON> resigned his congressional seat Sept. 6. As a delegate, he was allowed to vote in legislative committees but not on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> floor. Other members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> indicted since 1978: _ Rep <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON>, D-Tenn., charged in April 1987 with bank, mail and tax fraud No trial date has been set. _ Rep <PERSON> Bobbi </PERSON> <PERSON> Fiedler </PERSON>, R-Calif., indicted Jan. 23, 1986, along with an aide on charges she tried to buy off an opponent for the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> nomination in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> The charges subsequently were dismissed by a <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> judge in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Fiedler </PERSON> lost the primary. _ Rep <PERSON> Ge