<HEAD>Vietnam Commutes Death Penalty for Two Buddhist Monks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANBERRA, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Vietnamese authorities have bowed to international appeals and commuted the death sentences of two <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> monks convicted of subversive activities, an Australian government spokesman said today. Authorities in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> told <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>'s ambassador in <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> on Friday that the sentences of philosopher and teacher <PERSON> Thich </PERSON> <PERSON> Tue </PERSON> <PERSON> Si </PERSON> and scholar <PERSON> Thich </PERSON> <PERSON> Tri </PERSON> <PERSON> Sieu </PERSON> were commuted to 20 years in prison, the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> official said. The two monks were condemned to death in October by the <ORGANIZATION> Ho </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Minh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on charges they participated in subversive activities, the spokesman said on condition of anonymity. The two monks were arrested in 1984 with 19 <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> scholars. The scholars received undisclosed terms of imprisonment. There were no details on what kind of subversive activities they were alleged to have undertaken. The status of a third person also facing capital punishment in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Tran </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Luong </PERSON>, was not known, the spokesman said. He said <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> and other countries began making pleas to <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> after the death sentences were imposed. <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> opposes capital punishment.
