<HEAD>Cigarette Price To Go Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government raised cigarette prices today, saying it wants to discourage heavy smoking and bring prices more in line with production costs. The official <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> news agency on Sunday announced increases of 10.9 percent for all Polish-made cigarettes and 12.1 percent for imported brands. Health officials have increasingly expressed concern about heavy smoking among Poles. Cigarette consumption in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> rose by nearly a third between 1965 and 1985. Polish cigarettes cost an average of about 25 cents per pack. The average monthly salary in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> is about $ 100 at the official exchange rate.
