<HEAD>Brokerage, Urban League, Offer Inner-City Scholarships To Prevent
Dropouts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> today promised 250 first graders in 10 cities full college scholarships or cash incentives if they stay in school through graduation. The <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, the charitable arm of the nation's largest brokerage firm, is underwriting the new `` ScholarshipBuilder'' program with an initial $ 500,000 contribution, or $ 2,000 per student, to cover college tuitions estimated to reach $ 17,500 by the year 2000, when this year's first-graders will enter Students preferring jobs or the military would still get a one-time $ 1,000 cash payment to cover clothing and travel expenses, provided they graduate from high school. `` You are the hope for our future,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> chairman <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schreyer </PERSON> in remarks prepared for delivery today at <PERSON> Rafael </PERSON> <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON> @ <ORGANIZATION> Langston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hughes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elementary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harlem </LOCATION>, one of the 16 schools chosen. `` That is why we are investing now in your higher education. In return we want you to stay in school, to study well, to be free to dream important dreams, and to know that you can make them come true.'' In addition to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the schools are in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. A school in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> is to be named shortly, according to <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION>. Other corporations and philanthropists have offered similar incentives to persuade inner city children to stay in school. Philanthropist <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Lang </PERSON>, for example, promised 61 <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harlem </LOCATION> sixth-graders full college scholarships if they stayed in school. A group of businessmen called the `` 100 Black Men of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>'' is acting as mentors to a class of 28 ninth-graders and is guaranteeing their college expenses. But <PERSON> Schreyer </PERSON> said `` ScholarshipBuilder'' is different from other such `` adopt-a-class'' programs: `` Our program begins earlier in the child's educational career _ first grade _ and provides funds not only for college or other post-secondary education but also a stipend upon high school graduation for students who immediately become fully employed or who enter military service.'' The foundation's future annual contribution could go up or down to meet projected average college costs. But foundation president <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzgerald </PERSON> estimated his fund would eventually contribute about $ 8 million, which could appreciate to $ 16 million through investments by the time students are old enough to draw upon it. The Urban League chose inner city schools that ranked high in orderliness, attendance rates, parental involvement and other `` effectiveness'' measures. Students were chosen at random but with an eye toward achieving ethnic and racial balance. The league will continue to administer the scholarship program, including keeping tabs on youngsters' progress. Asked whether <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> would give preference to those students who eventually wanted careers on <LOCATION> Wall </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Street </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Fitzgerald </PERSON> said: `` I would say without committing us that we would, if they were qualified.'' The 15 other schools selected are: Capitol View Elementary, <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>; <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON> <PERSON> Elementary </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Overton </PERSON> <PERSON> Elementary </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Goodale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elementary </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION> James </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> R. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elementary </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>; 74th <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Earlington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Heights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elementary </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Floral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Heights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elementary </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON> <PERSON> Elementary </PERSON>, <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Elementary </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Liberty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elementary </ORGANIZATION>, Lorah Park Elementary, <ORGANIZATION> Olinda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elementary </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Orchard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Villa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elementary </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>; and <ORGANIZATION> Hendley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGA