<HEAD>Three `Skinheads' Arrested in Beating Death of Ethiopian Immigrant</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of Mieske sted Miske throughout; UPDATES
throughout with new information, background; no pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three men belonging to a `` skinhead'' gang were charged in connection with the beating death of an Ethiopian immigrant a week ago, police said Sunday. <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Mieske </PERSON>, 23, <PERSON> Kyle </PERSON> <PERSON> Brewster </PERSON>, 19, and <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Strasser </PERSON>, 20, were charged in what police said was a racially motivated and unprovoked attack on <PERSON> Mulugeta </PERSON> <PERSON> Seraw </PERSON>, 27, who had just been dropped off by friends in front of his home. The friends, who tried to intervene, suffered minor injuries. <PERSON> Seraw </PERSON> died a short time after the beating, in which his attackers used a baseball bat. <PERSON> Mieske </PERSON> and <PERSON> Brewster </PERSON> were charged with murder and remained in custody, said Detective <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON>. Bond for <PERSON> Strasser </PERSON>, charged with second-degree assault, was set at $ 100,000, <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Mieske </PERSON>, who also uses the alias `` <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Death </PERSON>,'' was arrested early Saturday, and <PERSON> Brewster </PERSON> and <PERSON> Strasser </PERSON> were arrested about noon Sunday, he said. The three were to appear in district court Monday afternoon. <PERSON> Mieske </PERSON> and <PERSON> Brewster </PERSON> face additional charges of assault and racial intimidation in a Sept. 10 incident at a grocery store, <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON> said. A black security guard and several store employees forcibly ejected a large number of `` skinheads'' about 11 p.m. that evening. In another charge that resulted from the homicide investigation but was unrelated to <PERSON> Seraw </PERSON>'s death, police and the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> arrested <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Barrett </PERSON>, 20, and charged him with unlawful flight to avoid prosecution and escape, <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON> said. The charge relates to a <LOCATION> Redwood </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, case involving vandalism to a place of worship, he said. The Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith said recently that reports of violent crimes have surfaced in every area where skinhead groups have organized. The civil rights group estimated in October there were about 2,000 young people actively involved in skinhead gangs in 21 states, but noted that many youngsters who adopt the skinhead look reject the racist element. The skinhead subculture emerged in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> as early as the 1960s. Segments of the movement took on <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> overtones in 1985 and since have been supported by and associated with the white supremacist <ORGANIZATION> Aryan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Youth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> and White Aryan Resistance. <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION> has a skinhead group of about 20 called East Side White Pride, with ties to the White Aryan Resistance, according to the league. It also has a group called Preservation of the White American Race, with about 10 members, half of whom are women, and a suburban group, Youth of <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>, the league said. Although police identified the suspects as part of a skinhead gang, officers did not identify any group by name.
