<HEAD>Cathedral's Plan To Sell Medieval World Map Stirs Anger</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The prelate of <ORGANIZATION> Hereford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cathedral </ORGANIZATION>, which is crumbling for lack of cash, has provoked a heated dispute among churchmen and art experts by putting one of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s greatest medieval treasures on sale. The 708-year-old <ORGANIZATION> Mappa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mundi </ORGANIZATION>, Latin for map of the world, has been kept in the cathedral for centuries and is to be auctioned by <PERSON> Sotheby </PERSON>'s in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> in June. News reports put its value at more than $ 4.5 million. The sale announcement Wednesday prompted a leading member of the cathedral's fund-raising committee to resign in protest. Newspapers have published angry editorials against the sale, and <ORGANIZATION> Hereford </ORGANIZATION> town leaders have vowed to fight it. The map shows historical events, Bible stories, topography, animals, plants and 420 cities on a 6-by-4 sheet of vellum. <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> is at the center of the map while <ORGANIZATION> Hereford </ORGANIZATION>, 144 miles northwest of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, is drawn on one edge. The controversy illuminates the dilemma faced by custodians of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s national heritage. The 900-year-old cathedral in <LOCATION> Hereford </LOCATION> is one of many in need of cash, but sales of treasures such as the <ORGANIZATION> Mappa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mundi </ORGANIZATION> threaten to put the nation's historical heritage into the hands of foreign buyers and remove them from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. The Dean of <LOCATION> Hereford </LOCATION>, the Very Rev. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Haynes </PERSON>, said in announcing the sale of the map that cathedral authorities need to clear a $ 273,000 overdraft and spend millions more on repairs, more staff, the cathedral's choir and new premises for its library of medieval books. Announcing his resignation from the fund-raising committee, Sir <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Strong </PERSON>, a former director of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Portrait </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gallery </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Victoria </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Museum </PERSON>, said Thursday, `` I was very upset to see the Dean standing outside his cathedral and holding up the <ORGANIZATION> Mappa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mundi </ORGANIZATION>, its finest treasure, for sale to the world. `` If that is the kind of church they are running, I no longer want to be associated with it.'' Replied <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Champion </PERSON>, chairman of the cathedral's appeal committee: `` I am sorry he feels the way that he does ... Put bluntly, it is a choice of what is more important, continuing the work of the cathedral ... or retaining a marvelous medieval treasure.'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Newman </PERSON>, deputy mayor of <LOCATION> Hereford </LOCATION>, a town of 48,000, said he wants <PERSON> Queen </PERSON> <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>, as secular head of the Church of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, to intervene. The map `` may legally be the cathedral's, but morally it belongs to the citizens of <LOCATION> Hereford </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Newman </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Sotheby </PERSON>'s says that as a national treasure, the <PERSON> Mappa </PERSON> <PERSON> Mundi </PERSON> is equivalent to <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s 11th century <ORGANIZATION> Bayeux </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tapestry </ORGANIZATION> depicting the invasion of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> by <PERSON> William </PERSON> the Conqueror in 1066. <PERSON> Georgina </PERSON> <PERSON> Nayler </PERSON>, deputy director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Heritage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Memorial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION>, said: `` We are outraged that one of the most important documents in the world is about to be put into an auction room.'' Lord <PERSON> Gowrie </PERSON>, <PERSON> Sotheby </PERSON>'s chairman, strongly denies allegations that no effort was made to find a British buyer. `` I am sorry that national institutions have not felt able to buy this great map,'' said <PERSON> Lord </PERSON> <PERSON> Gowrie </PERSON>, adding that he spent more than a year seeking a buyer among government-funded bodies such as the British Library. The <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday that chances of the map staying in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> appear slim. Critics accuse Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s Conservative administration of starving the arts of adequate government funding. The government favors sponsorship of the arts by private industry. Dr. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gem </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Cathedrals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> for <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> was quoted by <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> as saying many other cathedrals in financial trouble may have to sell off `` very important treasures.''
