<FIRST>r a PM-Drought-TheChases-V Bjt   11-21 0912</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drought-The Chases-V, Bjt,0938</SECOND>
<HEAD>Part V: Fall's Flooded Fields End 1988 With Sad Irony</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 This is the final installment of an occasional series that has told the story of the Drought of'88 through the eyes of one farm family, the Chases of <LOCATION> Barry </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By LISA PERLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HASTINGS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Chase </PERSON> prayed for rain all summer long. Now they pray for just a few days of sunshine. In June, when hot, dry winds blew the dusty dirt off seeds that would n't germinate _ when the worst dry spell since the Dust Bowl of the 1930s left crops withered and stunted _ the Chases never expected their fields would be too muddy at harvest time. `` We've never seen a year like this,'' <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Chase </PERSON> says, shaking his head. `` We've gone from the worst drought in 50 years to one of the wettest and coldest Octobers ever. One extreme to the other.'' From April 1 through mid-July, the Chases' 1,100-acre cash-crop and dairy farm in southwest <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Barry </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> received barely an inch of rain. Since Aug. 1, about 18 inches of rain and an inch of snow have pounded the weak stalks of corn and wilted soybeans _ more than twice the normal amount of precipitation. The Chases are n't alone. Many of the same <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> farmers who struggled through the summer's devastating drought were taunted by rains that came too late to do any good. The recent downpours, which have forced many farmers to delay harvesting their shriveled crops, bring the year to a sad, ironic close. This will be the first time in the Chases' 18 years of farming that they will have no crop to sell. Everything they harvest will be needed to feed their 300 head of beef and dairy cattle. With only about half a silo full of high-moisture corn _ enough to last about three months _ the Chases will have to buy from other farmers. `` A year like this makes you realize more than ever that the weather is the farmer's biggest friend or worst enemy,'' <PERSON> Chase </PERSON> says, sinking into a recliner in the couple's living room. He and his wife, both 51, estimate they lost about half their corn and soybean crop, and all of the string beans they were growing for a canning company. Their wheat crop was harvested before the drought hit in May. But the Chases do n't complain. `` At the height of the drought, you wondered whether you'd have anything at all,'' <PERSON> Chase </PERSON> says with a shrug. The loss of their cash crop represents a 30-percent cut in the Chases' income. To compound their financial plight, their expenses have been 20 percent higher than normal, mostly because of the money they spent on irrigation. But because irrigation only helps when there's some rainfall, `` we got zero out of that,'' <PERSON> Chase </PERSON> says in disgust, recalling the summer nights he and his son, <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON>, spent in the fields baby-sitting the irrigation system so that no water was wasted. The Chases are thankful their dairy herd, which represents about 60 percent of the farm's income, is healthy and productive. The income they make on their cash crop usually covers their operating expenses and pays for the 700 acres of land they rent _ about $ 75,000 this year. `` It's really frightening,'' <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Chase </PERSON> says. `` We do n't know where we'll get it, but it'll work out. ... We do n't dwell on it because it reminds us how horrible that loss really is.'' The Chases also are thankful they have an understanding lender. They're waiting to find out if they qualify for the federal government's $ 3.9 billion drought-relief aid program. But they ca n't help but think back to their early spring projections. On paper, this looked like it was going to be the family's most prosperous year ever. After managing to save their farm from foreclosure three years ago by deeding to the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> and leasing it back _ parcel by parcel _ the Chases expected this year would be the one to pay off a sizable chunk of the debt they had accumulated. Now, all they'd like to do is finish harvesting by Thanksgiving _ a goal they've met every year. It seems unlikely this time. The Chases, who are in a partnership with son <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> and daughter-in-law <PERSON> Dena </PERSON>, pray for clear skies in order to harvest the remaining acres of corn and soybeans. Every time it rains _ or snows _ several dry days must follow before it's safe to take equipment out in the fields. They've already had equipment stuck in the mud twice `` Now all we can do is pray for a freeze,'' <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Chase </PERSON> says. `` But if it snows first, that'll just insulate it and it'll stay wet.'' And if the fields are n't harvested in the fall, it means more work in the spring because the fields would have to be cleared before planting. Meanwhile, the corn still standing in the brown, muddy fields is growing moldy, rendering it useless as feed for the cattle. And with each pounding rain, more of the weak crop is ruined. Still, the Chases look ahead with hope. `` I guess the thought of giving up does n't enter my mind,'' <PERSON> Chase </PERSON> says. `` Even though it has been a very trying year and very frustrating, we have a lot to be thankful for and we survive because we know next year will be better.''
</TEXT>
