<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President-elect <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, faced with unease in the financial markets over the gaping budge deficits, today will name <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Darman </PERSON> to run <ORGANIZATION> OMB </ORGANIZATION> and tap <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Boskin </PERSON> as chief financial adviser, transition sources say. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> scheduled a morning news conference today to make what his office described only as an announcement about the transtion. But sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the president-elect has enlisted <PERSON> Darman </PERSON> as director of the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Boskin </PERSON> as chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisers </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Darman </PERSON> was the right arm of <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> throughout the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, both when <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> was White House chief of staff and later as <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> secretary. He played a behind-the-scenes role in negotiating the 1983 rescue plan for Social Security. <PERSON> Darman </PERSON> was a whiz kid for <PERSON> Elliot </PERSON> <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON> as secretary of health, education and welfare in the early 1970s. <PERSON> Boskin </PERSON> is a well-known conservative economist and expert on the Social Security system. He was a father of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s `` flexible freeze'' idea to drive down the deficit in four years. The stock market has sagged and the value of the dollar fallen since <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> captured the White Hous