<FIRST>r a PM-RosierTrial     11-21 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rosier Trial,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Expects to Complete Mercy Killing Case By Thanksgiving</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT LEISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Less than a year after the death of his cancer-stricken wife, Dr. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosier </PERSON> shocked television viewers when he admitted, `` I administered something to terminate her life.'' Now the 47-year-old <PERSON> Fort </PERSON> <PERSON> Myers </PERSON> pathologist is on trial here on charges of first-degree murder, attempted murder and conspiracy to commit murder in the Jan. 15, 1986, death of <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosier </PERSON>, his wife of 23 years. Mrs. <PERSON> Rosier </PERSON>, 43, suffered from lung cancer, which doctors say had spread to other organs. The state contends the interview, broadcast Nov. 12, 1986, amounted to a confession. <PERSON> Rosier </PERSON> admitted his wife did n't die of cancer. He said she wanted to die before the situation became horrible and that he merely helped her on her way. `` There was no question <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosier </PERSON> wanted to end her life,'' said Assistant State Attorney <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Volz </PERSON>, who expects to finishing presenting his case before Thanksgiving. The trial, now in its fourth week, was moved from <LOCATION> southwest </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> because of extensive pretrial publicity. <PERSON> Rosier </PERSON> gave his wife 20 pills of <LOCATION> Secanol </LOCATION> _ a strong sedative _ and when that did n't work, he gave her morphine injections, then morphine suppositories, prosecutors said. During the trial, however, Mrs. <PERSON> Rosier </PERSON>'s stepfather, <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> <PERSON> Delman </PERSON>, has described in detail how he smothered her after Rosier's botched attempts `` I decided to gently cover her nose and mouth,'' <PERSON> Delman </PERSON> testified, demonstrating on himself for the jury. `` I did n't give it a second thought ... I did n't get any pulse ... I did n't hear any more sound.'' <PERSON> Delman </PERSON>, 68, a retired <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> dentist, said he was afraid she might become a `` vegetable'' after <PERSON> Rosier </PERSON> left her unconscious and lingering near death for 12 hours. `` He obviously did n't do such a good job,'' <PERSON> Delman </PERSON> said, adding that he decided, `` Enough is enough.'' He testified as a key state witness under a grant of immunity. No charges were filed against him because he and his two sons, <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> and <PERSON> Farrell </PERSON> <PERSON> Delman </PERSON>, successfully negotiated an immunity agreement before prosecutors knew the extent of their involvment. They are the state's star witnesses. The defense said the state was taken. `` This is not a murder case. It is wrongful prosecution,'' said defense attorney <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosenblatt </PERSON>, who has n't decided yet whether to put Rosier on the stand. `` Prosecution is a face-saving device.'' However, the state maintains it had no choice. Without the Delmans' testimony, there was very little on which to build a case. No autopsy was performed, and Mrs. <PERSON> Rosier </PERSON> was cremated 52 hours after her death. Even if they had known beforehand, prosecutors still would have extended immunity to the Delmans, testified <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzpatrick </PERSON>, lead investigator. `` It changed nothing,'' he said. <PERSON> Rosier </PERSON> `` orchestrated his wife's death. Through a prior arrangement, permitted in terminally ill cases, <PERSON> Rosier </PERSON> called the <ORGANIZATION> Lee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Examiner </ORGANIZATION>'s office and told coroners officials his wife was dying. She was placed on an expected death list. No autopsy would be necessary. A death certificate signed by one of her treating physicians attributed death to lung cancer, according to testimony. Attorneys for both sides agree the couple made a double suicide pact after Mrs. <PERSON> Rosier </PERSON>'s cancer was diagnosed in spring 1985. But <PERSON> Rosier </PERSON> did n't go through with it for the sake of his children, <PERSON> Jacob </PERSON>, now 19, and <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON>, 21, <PERSON> Volz </PERSON> said.
