$26.8 billion; include that management, Kolhberg undecided whether
to make new bids. No pickup. A longer version moved on financial
wire.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BILL MENEZES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Food and tobacco giant <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> on Sunday extended its deadline for buyout offers after a potential new bidder said it was considering making a record offer of up to $ 26.6 billion. The tentative proposal for <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> from a group led by the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and the <PERSON> Pritzker </PERSON> family of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> would be nearly double the biggest acquisition on record, <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 13.4 billion purchase of <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in 1984. The <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> proposal, its first expression of interest in the consumer goods giant, easily topped two sweetened offers made by <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> management and the buyout firm <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roberts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co.. <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION>, which is based in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, is the nation's 19th biggest industrial company, and the maker of hundreds of consumer items that range from <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuervo </PERSON> tequila and <LOCATION> Salem </LOCATION> cigarettes to Life Savers candy and Milk Bone dog snacks The offers disclosed Sunday top all previous bids, and a special <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> committee that is running the auction indicated that its decision to extend the bidding period could produce even higher offers. `` Due to the varying potential values and nature of the consideration offered in the two bids and the proposal, and the varying terms, conditions and contingencies associated with each, the special committee determined not to make any recommendation at this time'' regarding any of the proposals, said <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hugel </PERSON>, the committee's chairman. The five-member committee of <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION>'s board of directors also said it would accept bids through Nov. 29. The panel had initially cut off bidding at 5 p.m. last Friday. The preliminary offer by the <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston-Pritzker </ORGANIZATION> group would involve the acquisition in 1989 of <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION>'s tobacco business, which accounts for about 40 percent of its annual sales, followed by the installment sale of its food businesses. First <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> indicated the total consideration could range from $ 98 to $ 110 cash a share, plus securities and stock warrants valued at from $ 7 to $ 8 a share. The warrants would entitle <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> shareholders to acquire up to 20 percent of the tobacco business. At $ 118 a share, the maximum possible offer from the group would be $ 26.6 billion. The committee said the management-led group, which is allied with the investment firms <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Salomon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, had raised its offer to $ 100 a share in cash for 175 million of the company's 225.3 million outstanding common shares. The group said it would acquire the remaining shares for $ 56 cash, plus securities and common stock in the surviving company that it said would bring the total consideration to $ 100 a share. The common stock would equal about 15 percent of the surviving company's outstanding shares, according to the special committee The $ 100 a share offer values <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> at $ 22.5 billion. The management group's previous offer had been for $ 92 a share, or $ 20.7 billion. The new offer by <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION> _ which previously had offered $ 90 a share, or about $ 20.3 billion _ included $ 94 cash a share for about 178 million <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> shares, with the remaining shares to be exchanged for preferred stock and securities the firm valued at $ 94 a share, giving its offer an indicated value of about $ 21.2 billion. Management started the bidding a month ago when it announced it was considering a buyout offer, and <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION> quickly entered the fray with a competing bid. Both parties submitted firm offers to the <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> committee by Friday's deadline, but they said late Sunday they were undecided whether to make new offers.
