<HEAD>Dollar Holds Steady, Stock Prices Hit Another Record High</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing Nikkei, dollar. Picks up 4th graf pvs,
`The dollar ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar inched up against the Japanese yen Monday, while share prices rose moderately on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. The dollar closed at 122.52 yen, up 0.12 yen from Friday's close of 122.40 yen. Opening at 122.40 yen, the currency moved in a narrow range of 122.37 yen and 122.60 yen. The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 103.39-point winner Friday, added another 104.06 points or 0.36 percent to finish at 29,284.26, a new record high. On Friday, the index closed at 29,180.20. The dollar traded around its opening level in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> as the market turned increasingly cautious about selling the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency following concerted intervention Friday by the world's major central banks, said a dealer at the Bank of <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. Because of the extent of intervention Friday during both <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> dealings, there is no apparent force in the market now to push the dollar down further, he said, speaking on condition of anonymity. But he said upward momentum was also absent. `` Although the dollar-yen rate is stabilized for the moment, it does n't mean participants are willing to buy the dollar,'' he added. On the stock exchange, `` market players were interested in wide variety of issues,'' said an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Nomura </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s largest brokerage `` It's a sign that more people are looking for places to invest their money,'' he said, asking that he not be identified.
