<HEAD>Book: Lincoln Assassination A Confederate Intelligence Plot</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX DOMINGUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilkes </PERSON> <PERSON> Booth </PERSON> was n't a shiftless actor who killed <PERSON> Abraham </PERSON> <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON> out of despondency over the South's loss in the Civil War, but a Confederate intelligence agent, a new book contends. Confederate leaders sanctioned the assassination as a last-ditch effort toforce the North into peace negotiations, three former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> intelligence officers wrote in `` Come Retribution,'' recently published by the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Booth </PERSON> also used an underground intelligence network for his escape after shooting <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON> during a performance at <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s Theatre in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, on April 14, 1865, five days after Gen. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>'s surrender at <LOCATION> Appomattox </LOCATION>, the authors contend. `` The book challenges the long-held belief that, in the closing months of the Civil War, the Confederacy stubbornly held out against surrender even though it had no hope of winning its independence,'' <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Tidwell </PERSON>, one of the authors, wrote in a recent article. `` It shows instead that the Confederates had a well-developed plan for the campaign of 1865 which they believed would result in a Southern victory or at least a stalemate.'' The Confederacy had wanted to kidnap <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON>, but when that plan failed, it plotted to blow up the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Tidwell </PERSON> said. The bombing plan was aborted when a Confederate demolition expert was arrested, <PERSON> Tidwell </PERSON> said. Southern leaders finally decided to kill <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON>, demoralize the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> and begin a last ditch offensive, <PERSON> Tidwell </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>'s surrender of the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Northern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> had virtually ended the war by that time, but <PERSON> Booth </PERSON> thought he could save the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> by killing <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON>, said <PERSON> Tidwell </PERSON>, a retired <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> officer <PERSON> Tidwell </PERSON>'s co-authors are <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>, a retired <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official who served in <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> intelligence during World War II, and <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Winfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaddy </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> official. <PERSON> Tidwell </PERSON> said the three used their intelligence experience to re-examine the assassination and uncover what they alleged was a well-established Conferederate intelligence network. They examined thousand of documents in the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Archives </ORGANIZATION> over a 10-year period. `` Our evidence is largely circumstantial,'' <PERSON> Tidwell </PERSON> said. `` Basically, we are trying to tell our story by putting together many small pieces of information, each well documented.'' The authors contend <PERSON> Booth </PERSON> was not helped during his escape by strangers or a rag-tag band of sympathizers hastily assembled before the assassination. Instead, <PERSON> Booth </PERSON> appears to have followed the main Confederate underground network leading from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to the Confederate capital in <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, the book contends. Of the 17 who helped <PERSON> Booth </PERSON>'s escape, the authors were able to link 12 with the Confederacy, eight of whom had participated in Confederate intelligence activities. The authors also elaborate on the activities of a Southern intelligence operation that spied in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. The book's title comes from a code system the Confederate intelligence used in which a certain word or phrase was used to decipher messages. `` Come Retribution'' was the last code key used by Confederate intelligence, <PERSON> Tidwell </PERSON> said. A chart used to decipher the code was found among <PERSON> Booth </PERSON>'s effects after he was shot by Union soldiers 11 days after the assassination of <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON>.
