<HEAD>Product Safety Chairman Quitting For Think Tank Post</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Terrence </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Scanlon </PERSON>, a Democrat who has promoted voluntary safety programs as the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Consumer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Product </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, is resigning to take a post with a conservative think tank The <ORGANIZATION> Heritage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> said Sunday that <PERSON> Scanlon </PERSON> would become vice president and treasurer of the organization effective Jan. 3. One of the highest ranking Democrats in the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, <PERSON> Scanlon </PERSON> has run his agency with a philosophy close to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s emphasis on voluntary safety programs and cooperation with industry. Consumer advocates attacked his approach and urged promoting product safety more aggressively, but <PERSON> Scanlon </PERSON> responded that voluntary programs can be established more quickly than government regulations. `` You can do a voluntary standards approach at the same time you have an enforcement program,'' he said in a telephone interview. <PERSON> Scanlon </PERSON> said that under his leadership, the independent agency's civil penalties against companies violating safety standards reached an all-time high <PERSON> Scanlon </PERSON> cited as a major accomplishment of his tenure at the agency an agreement last year to cooperate with the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> in halting imports of unsafe products before they reach domestic store shelves. A former aide to Presidents <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> and <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Scanlon </PERSON> served in the <ORGANIZATION> Small </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> before he was appointed to the safety agency. He was the agency's chairman from December 1985 to December 1986, but had to relinquish the post when <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> failed to confirm his appointment within a year. The delay coincided with an investigation of charges that <PERSON> Scanlon </PERSON> had used the commission's staff for personal projects. He was exonerated of any criminal wrongdoing and was confirmed as commission chairman in July 1986. The commission consists of five members, and a quorum of three is needed to conduct business. Currently, only three commissioners are serving because <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has not provided funds for the two remaining positions. <PERSON> Scanlon </PERSON>'s departure would leave only <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> Dawson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> as commissioners, too few for the agency to conduct business. <PERSON> Scanlon </PERSON> will be in charge of fund raising and financial management at the <ORGANIZATION> Heritage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, which also has attracted several former <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration officials including former Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> and former <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> ambassador <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Lichtenstein </PERSON>.
