<HEAD>Trying To Cross Into United States, Canadian Learns He's A Criminal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ARNPRIOR, Ontario (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Schinkel </PERSON> says he did n't know he had a criminal record until he was barred entry into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. After a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> customs officer did a computer check, <PERSON> Schinkel </PERSON>, 41, was told there was a record of a narcotics offence _ cultivation of marijuana _ that meant he was n't allowed into the country. Four years ago, police seized two marijuana plants from <PERSON> Schinkel </PERSON>'s garden at his home in <LOCATION> White </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION>, near <LOCATION> Arnprior </LOCATION>. When he went to court, <PERSON> Schinkel </PERSON> received a conditional discharge and the judge told him he was a lucky man because he would n't have a criminal record. But the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> records as convictions all sentences handed down by <LOCATION> Canadian </LOCATION> courts _ discharges included. `` As far as we are concerned, a conditional discharge is the same thing as a conviction,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hogan </PERSON>, port director for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> immigration at <LOCATION> Alexandria </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION> `` We do n't recognize Canadian pardons either.'' <PERSON> Schinkel </PERSON>'s experience `` points out something pretty outrageous,'' said <LOCATION> Ottawa </LOCATION> lawyer <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Wakefield </PERSON>. `` The whole intent of the discharge provisions in Canadian law is to remove any stigma, any prejudice attached to the person involved. `` But what's really amazing here is we are supplying -LRB- <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials -RRB- with information about discharges, knowing it is being used in a manner that clearly undermines the intent of Canadian law.'' The legal hitch meant trouble for <PERSON> Schinkel </PERSON>, a woodworker. When he was refused entry to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in March at <LOCATION> Cornwall </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Schinkel </PERSON> _ determined not to cancel a <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> vacation _ tried again down the road at the Ivy <LOCATION> Lea </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bridge </LOCATION>, near <LOCATION> Gananoque </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION>. Another computer check showed <PERSON> Schinkel </PERSON> had tried to cross the border only a few hours before, and <PERSON> Schinkel </PERSON> says <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> customs officials held him for 4 -LCB- hours for questioning. He said he was was photographed, fingerprinted, and officials confiscated his girlfriend's pickup truck and sent him back across the bridge on foot to <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. Six months later, <PERSON> Schinkel </PERSON> says, he got the truck back after paying a $ 500 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> penalty.
