<HEAD>Three Party Leaders Seek Office Of Canadian Prime Minister</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Canada-Elections, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Under <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s parliamentary system, voters choose a member of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> from their district and do n't vote directly for a party leader. But three men symbolize their parties and stand to become prime minister.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> BRIAN </PERSON> <PERSON> MULRONEY </PERSON> He led the <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> to a smashing victory in 1984 and became prime minister. Born in <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION> of working-class <ORGANIZATION> Anglo </ORGANIZATION> parents, he is the first bilingual native of that French-speaking province to lead his party. The 49-year-old <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> eased smoothly from being a lawyer to his successful political career. He is a strong, emphatic public speaker. His term was marked by general economic prosperity during which more than 1 million jobs were created and inflation remained stable at about 4 percent. He was able to distance himself from eight Cabinet ministers who resigned in successive scandals. <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> started the campaign hoping to persuade voters to return him as the most competent leader, but the free trade pact he signed with President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> quickly became the No. 1 election issue.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> JOHN </PERSON> <PERSON> TURNER </PERSON> The 59-year-old <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> inherited the <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leadership from <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Trudeau </PERSON>, returning to politics as prime minister in 1984 after eight years as a corporate lawyer. He called an election two weeks later and was quickly ousted, serving as prime minister only 79 days. Turner survived three internal attempts to oust him as Liberal leader since 1984. He started this year's campaign with the Liberals in apparent disarray but forged ahead with his persistent attacks on the free trade agreement. <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> was born in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> but came to <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> as a child. He was <PERSON> Trudeau </PERSON>'s finance minister from 1972 to 1975, and opponents call him the father of the modern Canadian deficit for allowing government spending to rise substantially. His home district is in <LOCATION> Vancouver </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> ED </PERSON> <PERSON> BROADBENT </PERSON> A political science professor turned politician, <PERSON> Broadbent </PERSON> now has led his party in four national elections. His integrity and personal credibility have helped the New Democrats build their strongest national profile ever. At the outset of the campaign, there even was talk that they could finish second to become the official opposition. Yet the Liberals' revival appears to have pushed back the New Democrats to their traditional, third-place role. <PERSON> Broadbent </PERSON>, 52, opposes the free trade agreement but tried to campaign on a broader platform on issues such as day care and the environment. The New Democrats claim to represent the average Canadian more than the other parties, which they charge are beholden to other interests. <PERSON> Broadbent </PERSON> is from <LOCATION> Oshawa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION>, an auto center just east of <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
