<HEAD>Canadian Election At A Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Canada-Elections, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are some facts and figures on the Canadian election:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 THE STAKES _ Canadians are electing a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commons </ORGANIZATION> newly expanded to 295 seats, so a party needs 148 seats to form a majority government.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 THE VOTERS _ There are 17.1 million eligible voters. Polls open from 9 a.m. to 8 p.m. in each district. Across the nation that means they open at 7:30 a.m. EST in <LOCATION> Newfoundland </LOCATION> and close at 11 p.m. EST in <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>. The first returns are expected about 9 p.m. EST, but it could be well into the night before the outcome is clear. Voter turnout in the last Canadian national election on Sept. 4, 1984, was 75 percent.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 THE MAJOR PARTIES _ They are the incumbent <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> led by Prime Minister <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON>, the opposition <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> led by <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> and the socialist <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> led by <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Broadbent </PERSON>. In 1984, the Conservatives won 211 seats, the Liberals 40, the New Democrats 30, and there was one independent. The House of Commons then had 282 seats.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 THE KEY ISSUE _ The free trade agreement with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> scheduled to take effect Jan. 1 overshadowed all other issues in the seven-week campaign. The Conservatives say the agreement will guarantee future Canadian prosperity by securing access to the larger <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market. The Liberals and New Democrats oppose the pact, saying it endangers Canadian sovereignty and such crucial social programs as senior pensions and health care. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has approved the agreement, but it still needs final Canadian parliamentary approval. Only a <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> majority government ensures that the agreement will proceed.
</TEXT>
