<HEAD>Companies Encourage Workers To Support Free Trade On Eve Of
Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Canada-Elections, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One of <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s largest supermarket chains is encouraging its workers to back the U.S.-Canadian free trade pact, joining several other companies using similar tactics to try to affect today's elections. Along with their paychecks last Thursday, <ORGANIZATION> Loblaws </ORGANIZATION> workers received a seven-page letter from company president <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> supporting the free trade accord with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The Loblaws letter claims the deal, which requires Canadian parliamentary ratification, could knock 8,000 Canadian dollars -LRB- $ 6,480 -RRB- off the price of a house `` or an extra $ 20 -LRB- Canadian -RRB- off the price of winter coats for the kids this year.'' The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has already approved the measure. At least one worker thinks the letter is an attempt to intimidate employees into voting for the Progressive Conservatives, the governing party and architects of the controversial deal. The Liberals and <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> oppose the pact. `` They should give people free choice. That's the way it's supposed to be,'' one <ORGANIZATION> Loblaws </ORGANIZATION> worker was quoted as telling the <ORGANIZATION> Toronto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> newspaper. `` I do n't think they should do anything like that A company spokesman denied the letter is meant to sway workers into voting for the Conservatives. `` It was a personal message that was meant to be non-political in nature,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Arnett </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Loblaws </ORGANIZATION> vice-president of merchandising and development. The retail giant, which employs 33,000 workers at stores across the country, is one of several large corporations to have entered the free-trade debate by calling on workers to support the deal. <ORGANIZATION> Stelco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Hamilton </LOCATION> steel manufacturer with 12,500 employees, and <ORGANIZATION> Canadair </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION> aircraft company, have distribted similar letters to their workers. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> made a video of president <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrington </PERSON> defending the deal. The tapes were sent to the company's factories in <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION>, said spokesman <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartman </PERSON>. Some plants chose not to show the video to employees, he added. Several other companies have distributed pro-free trade leaflets produced by the <ORGANIZATION> Canadian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> and Job Opportunities.
