<SECOND>Three `Skinheads' Arrested in Black's Beating Death</SECOND>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three members of a `` skinhead'' gang have been arrested and charged in what police say was a racially motivated and unprovoked attack that killed a black man in front of his home. <PERSON> Mulugetta </PERSON> <PERSON> Seraw </PERSON>, a 27-year-old Ethiopian immigrant, was kicked in the head and beaten with a baseball bat by his assailants, and died shortly after the Nov. 13 attack. The three men charged are members of East Side White Pride, the state's largest skinhead gang, said <LOCATION> Multnomah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schrunk </PERSON>. Witnesses said <PERSON> Seraw </PERSON>'s attackers had shaven heads and wore green military jackets with <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> flags on the sleeve. <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Mieske </PERSON>, 23, whose alias is `` <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Death </PERSON>,'' and <PERSON> Kyle </PERSON> <PERSON> Brewster </PERSON>, 19, were being held without bond on murder charges pending arraignments this afternoon, said homicide Detective <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Strasser </PERSON>, 20, was charged with second-degree assault and was being held on $ 100,000 bail. <PERSON> Mieske </PERSON> was arrested early Saturday and the two others Sunday, said authorities, who did not say how they tracked the three down. East Side White Pride has about 20 hard-core members, according to a report last month from the Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith, which monitors the activities of right-wing extremist organizations. The skinhead subculture emerged in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> as early as the 1960s. Segments of the movement took on <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> overtones in 1985 and since have been supported by and associated with the white supremacist <ORGANIZATION> Aryan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Youth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> and White Aryan Resistance. <PERSON> Mieske </PERSON> and <PERSON> Brewster </PERSON> face additional charges of first-degree assault and racial intimidation in a Sept. 10 disturbance at a grocery store on the city's southwest side, <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON> said. In that case, <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlyle </PERSON>, 25, a black security guard, and several store employees were drawn into a scuffle when they attempted to eject a large number of `` skinheads,'' authorities said. It was during the Seraw investigation that police were able to gather enough evidence to charge the pair in that case, <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON> said. A fourth person, who lived at the same address as <PERSON> Strasser </PERSON>, was arrested on a fugitive warrant from <LOCATION> Redwood </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON> said. The warrant charged <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Barrett </PERSON>, 20, with unlawful flight to avoid prosecution and escape in the Nov. 14, 1987, vandalism of Temple <PERSON> Beth </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacob </PERSON>. The synagogue had been spray-painted with racist slogans linked to the <ORGANIZATION> Aryan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Youth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> based neo-Nazi group that is known to have been recruiting skinheads in the <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION> area.
