<FIRST>r a PM-Retarded-Services     11-21 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Retarded-Services,0434</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Bars Phila. From Cutting Aid to Retarded</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge has barred the city and state from cutting off services to 9,000 retarded Philadelphians who live at home, saying the `` irrational'' decision threatened the recipients' health and safety. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Broderick </PERSON> issued a permanent injunction forbidding <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> and the state from eliminating vocational, family-support, early-intervention, recreational and case-management services to mentally retarded people who live with their families. In his ruling Thursday, the judge said that to deprive mentally retarded people of services they need for living and working would result in `` irreparable injury'' and `` cause serious regression to many.'' He also said it would violate the equal-protection and due-process clauses of the Constitution. The order will continue until further notice from the court, the judge said. A projected $ 6.8 million shortage in state funds prompted the city in June to announced plans to reduce or eliminate services for mentally retarded Philadelphians who live at home and are registered with the city for mental-retardation assistance. Services for mentally retarded people in state-funded group homes were not affected. The judge ruled that the city's decision affecting services to the retarded living at home and not to those living in state-funded residences was arbitrary. `` There has been a lack of judgment ... an irrational lack of fairness. The Constitution demands that defendants should have found a better way to resolve the problem,'' <PERSON> Broderick </PERSON> wrote. The judge did not say whether the city or state must fund the services. He did note, however, that the city `` has contributed $ 3 million annually in excess of its 10 percent match.'' State law requires the state to provide 90 percent of the funding for such services and counties are to pay 10 percent and provide the services themselves. In July, 32 people and the <ORGANIZATION> Philadelphia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Handicapped </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Children </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, filed a class-action lawsuit against the city and state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Welfare </ORGANIZATION> alleging that the city's mentally retarded were being denied their rights to `` lifelong community support.'' <PERSON> Broderick </PERSON> issued a temporary restraining order, effective Aug. 1, that prohibited a cutback in services and later extended it until last Friday. The attorney for the plaintiffs, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferleger </PERSON>, hailed the ruling as `` a landmark.'' `` No court has ever held that there is a guaranteed right to community services for people with retardation living at home,'' Ferleger said. Deputy City Solicitor <PERSON> Guy </PERSON> <PERSON> Vilim </PERSON> said the city would review the opinion before deciding how to proceed.
</TEXT>
