<HEAD>Prosecutor Says Convictions Gut Philadelphia-New Jersey Mob</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The convictions of mob boss <PERSON> Nicodemo </PERSON> `` Little Nicky'' <PERSON> Scarfo </PERSON> and 16 associates have taken `` the guts out'' of a deadly Philadelphia-southern <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> crime family, a prosecutor says. A federal jury Saturday night convicted <PERSON> Scarfo </PERSON>, 59, and 16 associates in a racketeering conspiracy that included murder, drug dealing, loan-sharking and illegal gambling. `` One of the things that this case did was it broke the myth of the Mafia's invincibility,'' said assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Pichini </PERSON>. <PERSON> Pichini </PERSON> said the convictions crippled the crime family because of the number of defendants involved and their high rankings in the organization. `` With one conviction, we were able to take the guts out,'' <PERSON> Pichini </PERSON> said. Each defendant was found guilty on each of the two main conspiracy counts they faced. In addition, some were found guilty on other charges they faced individually. Sentencing was not immediately scheduled by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Antwerpen </PERSON>. All face possible sentences of from 40 to 55 years in prison. <PERSON> Scarfo </PERSON> is already in prison on an unrelated conviction. <PERSON> Scarfo </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Simone </PERSON>, said he would appeal the verdict, reached after 26 hours of jury deliberations. `` I think in terms of taking down the entire power structure of the family, this is the first time that that has really occurred,'' said <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON>, head of the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Organized Crime Strike Force in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. `` What we've done here is really stopped them.'' While other convicted mob leaders, such as the late <PERSON> Vito </PERSON> <PERSON> Genovese </PERSON>, continued to rule during jail terms, law enforcement officials said <PERSON> Scarfo </PERSON> does n't have the clout, influence or savvy to follow suit. `` I believe <PERSON> Scarfo </PERSON>'s days as a leader in organized crime are over,'' said Col. <PERSON> Clinton </PERSON> <PERSON> Pagano </PERSON>, superintendent of the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jersey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION>. However, <PERSON> Pichini </PERSON> and <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON> cautioned that the verdict does n't mean the end of organized crime in the area Because <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> has been lucrative, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York-based </LOCATION> mobsters may move in, <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Scarfo </PERSON> is serving a 14-year prison term for conspiring to extort $ 1 million from a <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> developer. He and six others still face conspiracy charges in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> in the 1985 gangland-style slaying of mob associate <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> `` Frankie Flowers'' <PERSON> D'Alfonso </PERSON>.
