uth </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, but not to his hometown in the south, where residents reportedly oppose his return. National Assembly hearings on abuses under the Chun government focused today on attempts to stifle press freedom. More than 700 journalists were blacklisted and many newspaper and broadcast operations were placed under state control by the Chun administration. <PERSON> Chun </PERSON> has been a virtual prisoner in his luxurious <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> house, guarded by hundreds of riot police to prevent attacks by dissidents. Opposition groups have held major protests and tried to march on his home to demand his arrest. President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> <PERSON> Tae-woo </PERSON>'s government is under criticism for trying to protect <PERSON> Chun </PERSON> and the government is trying to defuse public anger without being implicated in the furor. <PERSON> Yonhap </PERSON>, the South Korean news agency, said the government was considering a probe by prosecutors against <PERSON> Chun </PERSON> if his apology and surrender of property does not satisfy the public. There have been increasing numbers of street protests urging <PERSON> Chun </PERSON>'s arrest in recent weeks. Over the weekend, thousands of students and dissidents battled riot police in downtown <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> after police stopped a march to <PERSON> Chun </PERSON>'s house. <PERSON> Chun </PERSON>, a former general, took power with military backing in 1980. He was succeeded by <PERSON> Roh </PERSON>, another former general and a close <PERSON> Chun </PERSON> associate.
