<HEAD>Judge Lets Stand $700,000 Verdict Against Newspapers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A judge has refused to set aside a $ 700,000 award against two newspapers, saying they committed `` calculated misdeeds'' when they published a source's name after promising him confidentiality. Officials of the <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paul </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pioneer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dispatch </ORGANIZATION>, the state's largest papers, said they were not surprised by Saturday's ruling and would appeal. The case concerns a suit filed by <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>, who claimed during trial in July that he lost his advertising job after the newspapers misrepresented and breached an oral contract they made to keep his name out of a politically sensitive story. <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> had leaked court documents to reporters during the 1982 gubernatorial campaign that revealed that <PERSON> Marlene </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, a candidate for lieutenant governor, had been arrested for shoplifting several years earlier. <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>, who worked for rival gubernatorial candidate <PERSON> Wheelock </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitney </PERSON>, provided the information on the condition that he not be identified as the source. Editors at the newspapers testified that they overruled their reporters' promises of anonymity because the public had the right to know the information came from the <PERSON> Whitney </PERSON> campaign. But Hennepin County District Judge <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> Knoll </PERSON> ruled that the First Amendment's guarantee of freedom of the press did not shield the newspapers against <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>'s breach of contract claim. `` The courts have made it clear that no First Amendment interest exists in protecting news media from calculated misdeeds,' `` Knoll's memorandum said. `` Certainly, the knowing and willful breach of a legally sufficient contract after hours of thought and discussion by corporate officers can fairly be characterized as a calculated misdeed.''' <PERSON> Knoll </PERSON> also dismissed the newspapers' argument that a relationship between a reporter and a source is anything other than commercial. `` The advertising war currently being waged by one -LRB- newspaper -RRB- against the other is ample evidence of the profit motive underlying their operations,'' he said. `` It's our intent to appeal,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Henry </PERSON>, publisher of the <ORGANIZATION> Pioneer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dispatch </ORGANIZATION>. `` We were hoping for a different outcome, but this was not unanticipated.'' <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> McGuire </PERSON>, managing editor of the <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION>, said his newspaper also will appeal the decision to the <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>.
