<HEAD>Brazilian Oil Workers End Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tens of thousands of oil workers today began returning to work after a 10-day nationwide walkout, the state oil monopoly <ORGANIZATION> Petrobras </ORGANIZATION> and strike leaders said. Local unions voted Sunday night to accept a government offer of wage increases, <ORGANIZATION> Petrobras </ORGANIZATION> press officer <PERSON> Lucio </PERSON> <PERSON> Pimentel </PERSON> said Monday. <PERSON> Mauro </PERSON> <PERSON> Costa </PERSON> of the national strike command in <LOCATION> Brasilia </LOCATION>, the capital, said some unions still were voting on the proposal, but `` the tendency is to accept the offer.'' `` It was a great political victory, although economically it did n't attain what we wanted,'' he said in a telephone interview. The strike by more than 50,000 petroleum workers paralyzed the nation's 11 refineries and caused severe shortages of cooking gas and diesel fuel. In weekend emergency meetings, the government offered strikers a 15 percent cost-of-living raise retroactive to June 1987 and 4 percent more for productivity. <ORGANIZATION> Petrobras </ORGANIZATION> agreed not to punish strikers and to discount only four days from their paychecks. Strike leaders urged unions to accept the offer, although it fell short of the 26.6 percent increase they were demanding. The government suspended cost-of-living raises last year, saying they fuel inflation now running at more than 1,000 percent a year. Oil workers earn an average $ 300 a month _ good wages by Brazilian standards. The strike forced the government to import emergency shipments of diesel fuel, cooking gas and kerosene. Gas rationing was imposed in some parts of the country. Brazilian refineries can produce 1.5 million barrels of petroleum by-products a day. The country consumes about 1.1 million barrels of oil daily, of which nearly 50 percent is imported.
