<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President-elect <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> announced today he will retain Attorney General <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>, saying the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> chief has `` a record of unquestioned integrity and a commitment to upholding the highest ethical standards.'' At a news conference, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he is appointing <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> because `` I know that he will work with me to fight drugs with every tool at our disposal'' and on other issues as well, including attacking crime `` at every level'' and defending the civil rights of all Americans. Since election day Nov. 8, a number of other names had emanated from the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> camp as possible replacements for <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>. In a brief interview at the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said that he had learned of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s decision to retain him at a weekend meeting initiated by the president-elect and that `` I was extremely pleased and gratified that he made this appointment.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s decision `` gives me the opportunity to continue what I hope will be a positive and productive course for the department,'' <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said in the interview. `` My priorities will be the president-elect's priorities.'' In addition to fighting drugs, <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said `` our efforts in ... white-collar crime, official corruption should be important to ensure high ethical standards in government and our business institutions.'' He singled out the environment and civil rights as other areas warranting attention. <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>, 56, has been in the Cabinet only since Aug. 12, when he succeeded <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, who resigned at the conclusion of a 14-month criminal investigation of his affairs. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> declared he had been vindicated. But the independent counsel who conducted the probe, while deciding not to seek an indictment, said <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> probably had twice broken a federal conflict-of-interest law and violated tax laws. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, asked the day after he was elected president if he would keep on <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> and several other <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> Cabinet members considered to be `` <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> people,'' did not answer directly. He said that `` some people at various levels may be asked to remain,'' but that `` there is something to be said for reinvigorating the process by, with new people.'' Indeed, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> insiders had sent mixed signals about the future of <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>, who was said to be eager to keep his job. At one point, those insiders had gone out of their way to discourage reports that his reappointment was assured. Other names that had been tossed about as possible replacements for <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> were <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruckelshaus </PERSON>, a former deputy at Justice and former <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> administrator, and <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>. In taking over the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>, a former governor of <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>, had vowed to `` make drug trafficking and drug abuse Public Enemy No. 1.'' <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> headed the department's criminal division during the <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> administration and established the agency's public integrity section, which prosecutes corrupt public officials.
