<HEAD>Kosovo Calm, Leaders Renew Campaign For More Control</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SLOBODAN LEKIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 4,000 ethnic Albanians today defied threats of a crackdown on street demonstrations and marched to the capital of the restive province of <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pristina </LOCATION> television said. Leaders of the republic of <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION> renewed their campaign for more control of <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> province following a wave of protests. In the liberal northern republic of <LOCATION> Slovenia </LOCATION>, meanwhile, an estimated 10,000 people held a peaceful rally in driving snow to demand a referendum on controversial constitutional amendments. <LOCATION> Pristina </LOCATION> television said today's crowds marched from <LOCATION> Orohovac </LOCATION>, 40 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Pristina </LOCATION>, to demand reinstatement of two ethnic <PERSON> Albanian </PERSON> leaders who were forced to resign under Serbian pressure last week. Police outside <LOCATION> Pristina </LOCATION> shepherded the crowd as it passed through the predominatly Serb suburb of <ORGANIZATION> Kosovo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Polje </ORGANIZATION>, the state-run <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> news agency said. No clashes between the rival groups were reported. The demonstrations in the southern province of <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>, involving up to 100,000 people last weekend, have been the biggest there since World War II. The protesters have been angered by the forced resignations last Thursday of <PERSON> Azem </PERSON> <PERSON> Vlasi </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kacusa </PERSON> <PERSON> Jasari </PERSON>, two ethnic Albanians from <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>'s 13-member ruling Politburo. The provincial party leadership has promised to review the resignations of <LOCATION> Vlasi </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Jasari </PERSON> at a meeting later this week. Asked why the the protesters had decided to defy warnings from numerous Communist party leaders against more protests, student <PERSON> Skelzen </PERSON> <PERSON> Malici </PERSON> said, `` We are aware of this, but we intend to continue coming here until the -LRB- two leaders -RRB- are reinstated.'' Serbian Communist leader <PERSON> Slobodan </PERSON> <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON>, who has led the campaign for more Serbian control of <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>, appeared to reject protesters' demands that the two ethnic <PERSON> Albanian </PERSON> leaders be reinstated. In a speech to Serbian Communist leaders in <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON> made no direct reference to the <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> protests, but said ethnic Albanian youths, who made up the majority of the protesters, are `` victims of indoctrination.'' `` The ideologues of counterrevolution should be held responsible and not those who are just their arm,'' he addded. He said that restoring Serbian control over the judiciary, schools and policing of <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> to stop alleged harassment of the Slav minority are `` a precondition for <LOCATION> Serbian </LOCATION> unity.'' <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON> said in his speech today that about 500 ethnic Albanians who have been jailed on charges of fomenting counterrevolution with alleged nationalism should be freed. `` We should let these people out of jail and jail those who are really responsible for the genocide and terror,'' he said. <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON> and his supporters commonly use terms such as `` genocide and terror'' when talking about the alleged harassment of <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Serb </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Montenegrin </LOCATION> minorities by ethnic Albanians. Official statistics show little if any evidence of ethnically motivated murder or proof of frequently alleged rapes of <LOCATION> Serbian </LOCATION> women by ethnic Albanian men. <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON>'s is campaigning for changes in the 1974 constitution that gave <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> broad autonomy. Communist leaders in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s other five republics see the campaign as part of a drive to increase the influence of <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION>, the largest republic, on the Yugoslav federation. But <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON> has said the changes would only put <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION> on an equal footing with other republics, which have no administrative provinces like <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Vojvodina </LOCATION>.
