<HEAD>Lithuanians Rally to Protest Lawmakers' Indecision on Autonomy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 19 grafs to UPDATE with Soviet lawmakers
recommending changes in amendments limiting power of republics. Pick
up 14th pvs, `Their ruling ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of Lithuanians chanting `` for shame!'' jammed the center of their capital <LOCATION> Vilnius </LOCATION> today to protest their legislature's refusal to declare the Sovutonomy from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, residents said. In <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, lawmakers recommended changes in constitutional amendments that have touched off the furor in <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION> and the other Baltic republics, iet republic's aEstonia and <LOCATION> Latvia </LOCATION>, because of limits they place on the republics' powers, the daily Pravda said. The amendments were proposed by Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> as the keystone of his political reform program, which includes the creation of a more powerful presidency and a full-time national legislature. In <LOCATION> Vilnuis </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Lithuanian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Perestroika </ORGANIZATION>'s call for a 10-minute noon protest halted traffic in the city center, and about 10,000 people rallied on the city's <LOCATION> Gediminas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION>, said movement spokeswoman <PERSON> Rita </PERSON> <PERSON> Dapkus </PERSON>. <PERSON> Alvydas </PERSON> <PERSON> Medalinskas </PERSON>, the movement's acting secretary, addressed the crowd from a balcony and called for the removal of three members of <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> Central Coithuanian words meaning `` for shame, for shame,'' to criticize the inaction of their republic's lawmakers, Ms. <PERSON> Dapkus </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Medalinskas </PERSON> told the crowd that what happened on Friday `` was detrimental not only to the -LRB- Lithuanian Perestroika -RRB- movement, but to all of <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION>,'' she said. The grassroots movement has called for another meeting of <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION>'s Supreme Soviet by Nov. 29, and is collecting signatures on petitions that call for such a session. What Ms. <PERSON> Dapkus </PERSON> called a `` symbolic strike'' was to last for 10 minutes throughout <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION>. She said traffic had come to a standstill in <LOCATION> Vilnius </LOCATION>, but there was no word yet from <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION>'s other cities Police in central <LOCATION> Vilnius </LOCATION> took no steps to interfere with the rally on Gediminas Square, she said. Ms. <PERSON> Dapkus </PERSON>, who is from <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, said she will be leaving the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> this week to set up an information bureau for the Lithuanian movement in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Pravda said today that a commission of the Supreme Soviet had recommended modifications in amendments to the Constitution that were proposed by <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and the national leadership as an apparent attempt to placate the Baltic republics. As originally written, the amendment to Article 108 authorizes a newly created <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION> to `` take decisions relative to the composition of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S.S.R. </ORGANIZATION>, the approval of the formation of new autonomous republics and autonomous regions in the composition of the union republics.'' The commission recommended that article be changed to limit the council to questions `` of national-state structure relative to the jurisdiction of the U.S.S.R.'' Article 108 also authorized the council to annul legislation and acts of the Soviet republics if they contradict the Constitution. The commission, which met Saturday, recommended that such language be stricken as part of an effort to increase `` the development of the sovereign rights of the republics,'' Pravda said. However, the lawmakers also condemned the action of the Estonian Supreme Soviet, saying its decision on Wednesday to give local laws primacy over Soviet legislation was at odds with the 1977 Soviet Constitution. Their ruling was transmitted to the Supreme Soviet Presidium, the nation's highest executive body, possibly presaging a striking down of the Estonian decision by the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> leadership. <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION> and the third <LOCATION> Baltic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> republic </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Latvia </LOCATION>, were independent after the 1917 Bolshevik revolution until 1940, when they were annexed by the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The small Westward-looking republics have used President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s political reforms _ dubbed `` perestroika'' _ to push for greater economic and cultural autonomy. Baltic residents contend that proposed amendments to the Soviet Constitution will limit their autonomy.
