Chicago, not dateline city.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DOWLING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> must hold a mayoral election next year to fill the two years remaining of the term of the late Mayor <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled today. The high court ruled without dissent. It said that a reading of state election law, along with the state law governing municipalities, requires that a special election be held to fill a vacancy that occurs with more than 28 months left on a four-year term. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, the city's first black mayor, died of a heart attack Nov. 25, 1987, with 3 -LCB- years left of his second term. `` The scheme recognizes the importance of the voters not to have a mayoral appointee who is not of their own choosing for more than 28 months,'' Justice <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Cunningham </PERSON> wrote in the court's opinion. A lower court ruling already has called for a primary Feb. 28, followed by a general election April 4. The decision was eagerly awaited by a crowded field of announced and unannounced mayoral candidates. Unannounced candidates include the incumbent acting mayor, <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON>, and front runner <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>, who were both said to be awaiting the ruling before announcing. Neither had any immediate comment after the ruling was handed down today. <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>, son of the late mayor <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> who died in 1976, just won a landslide re-election as <LOCATION> Cook </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> state's attorney and was the leader in a recent poll of potential mayoral contenders. `` That's no surprise. ... I never had any doubt that it would be 1989,'' said Democratic Alderman <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Burke </PERSON>, who has already announced his candidacy. `` We of course would have preferred that the question would have been cleared up a lot earlier.'' <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON>, who is black, was appointed acting mayor a year ago by a bitterly divided <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> after receiving the support of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s white council opponents. He has trailed in the mayoral polls to another black Democrat, <PERSON> Alderman </PERSON> <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, who has claimed to be <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s true political heir. In <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, a strongly Democratic town where no Republican has been mayor for more than a half-century, the primary is considered decisive. Many observers have said that if <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> split the black vote in the February primary, and other white candidates step aside, it could pave the way for a victory by <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>. The city's population is 40 percent black <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON>, 54, had supported the 1991 date, but has said repeatedly he is prepared to run a campaign immediately. Though <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>, 46, has declined to say whether he will run, close associates have been quoted as saying they expect him to make a bid. There are three other white candidates who have already announced, but two of them are considered likely to pull out if <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> runs. <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> lost to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> in a three-way <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> primary in 1983, when he and incumbent Mayor <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON> split the white vote. <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> today called the ruling `` a great victory'' for the people of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. Candidate <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Bloom </PERSON>, the white liberal alderman who was a staunch <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> ally, agreed. `` I think it's the decision the public wanted. They did n't want 29 members of the <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> to elect their mayor for three years,'' said <PERSON> Bloom </PERSON>. He is not considered to be much of a factor in the race but insists he's in it to the end.
