<HEAD>Lack of Accountability Helps Perpetuate Inefficiency</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS three grafs after 10th graf pvs, `Kintanar's host...'
with Aquino comment today. Picks up 12th graf pvs, `Mrs. Aquino...</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Lack of public accountability and an inefficient bureaucracy have created a nightmare of sinking ships, rebels who escape from birthday parties and foodstocks that vanish. Some problems which have beset the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> recently can be explained by bad luck, including three tropical storms that killed more than 600 people in two weeks. But others appear the result of appalling lack of organization, resources and efficiency in President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s administration Lack of public accountability contributes to an atmosphere where accidents wait to happen. That in turn may be undermining public confidence in government. A recent survey by <ORGANIZATION> Ateneo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> 1,200 people nationwide found just 31 percent expected their lives to improve. Forty-two percent expected conditions to remain the same and 17 percent said they would get worse. `` It is not enough that the president sets the example,'' wrote the <ORGANIZATION> Philippine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inquirer </ORGANIZATION> on the issue of accountability. `` She should also find the strength and conviction to make examples of officials who do not measure up.'' On Nov. 12, the alleged chief of the Communist rebel army escaped. The military says <PERSON> Romulo </PERSON> <PERSON> Kintanar </PERSON>, 41, and his wife <PERSON> Gloria </PERSON>, 38, walked away from a birthday party for the former stockade commandant. Acting stockade commander, Maj. <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Landrito </PERSON>, offered as an excuse that he was asleep in his office at the time. It was not the first security breach at the stockade. <PERSON> Kintanar </PERSON>'s host, Lt. Col. <PERSON> Robelito </PERSON> <PERSON> Comilang </PERSON>, was suspended last month when a right-wing officer jailed for a leading role in an August 1987 coup attempt reportedly walked through three doors that were supposed to be locked, climbed the stockade wall and was fatally shot by guards. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> today blamed the six military coup attempts that rocked her administration on her efforts to seek rapproachment with communist rebels during a 60-day cease-fire that expired in February 1987. `` The right-wing fringe of the military ... launched a succession of destabilizing attempts to topple me from power,'' she said. `` The assassination of leftist leaders discredited my commitment to human rights.'' In June, dozens of armed men tried to free former Gov. <PERSON> Orlando </PERSON> <PERSON> Dulay </PERSON>, jailed in the 1986 deaths of several <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> supporters. Raiders failed to free Dulay but made off with armory weapons. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> has demanded a full investigation into <PERSON> Kintanar </PERSON>'s escape Three senior officers, including <LOCATION> Landrito </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Comilang </PERSON>, have been relieved and restricted to quarters. But there is widespread skepticism about change. `` There has not been any real investigation, much less real punishment of people concerned,'' fumed Sen. <PERSON> Ernesto </PERSON> <PERSON> Maceda </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. `` There is a tendency to cover up. In the spirit of comradeship, they just cover up the incident to control the damage.'' <PERSON> Maceda </PERSON>'s doubts were based on the failure of previous investigations to fix responsibility, punish those at fault and implement changes. Commissions failed to solve the September 1986 assassination of labor leader <PERSON> Rolando </PERSON> <PERSON> Olalia </PERSON>, the August killing of Local Governments Secretary <PERSON> Jaime </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferrer </PERSON> and the September 1987 slaying of leftist leader <PERSON> Lean </PERSON> <PERSON> Alejandro </PERSON>. Another commission organized after the January 1987 killing of 13 land reform protesters by soldiers guarding the presidential palace never established who gave the order to fire. The senior officer on duty at the time, Brig. Gen. <PERSON> Ramon </PERSON> <PERSON> Montano </PERSON>, was furloughed as capital regional commander during the probe. But months later, he was promoted to major general and given command of the national police. Three separate commissions investigated the December 1987 collision of the passenger ship Dona Paz with the oil tanker, in which more than 3,000 people were believed to have perished. All three found evidence of widespread inefficiency in the maritime industry, including overloaded ships, lack of adequate communications, poorly trained crew and the absence of effective search and rescue procedures. But <PERSON> Commodore </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlito </PERSON> <PERSON> Cunanan </PERSON>, who as coast guard commandant was responsible for maritime safety, was promoted to navy commander after the Dona Paz disaster. Last month, the <PERSON> Dona </PERSON> <PERSON> Marilyn </PERSON>, another passenger ship owned by the same company, sailed into Typhoon Ruby and sank with 500 people aboard, about half of whom remain missing and feared dead. Although the investigations into the second sinking have not been completed, officials say they have found evidence of many of the same shortcomings which led to the Dona Paz disaster. `` The country is one big <PERSON> Dona </PERSON> <PERSON> Marilyn </PERSON> sinking in the middle of a storm while the captain snores on top of a mahjong table,'' wrote columnist <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Tatad </PERSON>. `` Many -LRB- heads -RRB- should roll.'' Lack of accountability has not been limited to the military. In September, Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> fired <PERSON> Emil </PERSON> <PERSON> Ong </PERSON> as chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> after two investigating committees found evidence of widespread incompetence. They cited, among other things, the disappearance of $ 350,000 worth of rice, which <PERSON> Ong </PERSON> said sank on three barges. The coast guard had no record of the sinking. Ong was furloughed during the investigations, then fired. Two days after he was dismissed for incompetence, <PERSON> Ong </PERSON> was named presidential adviser for regional government affairs. Also in September, retired Maj. Gen. <PERSON> Cesar </PERSON> <PERSON> Tapia </PERSON> quit as security chief of <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>'s international airport, claiming he was powerless to stop rampant corruption there. Despite his allegations, most customs and immigration officials remain on the job there.
</TEXT>
