<HEAD>Trade Officials to Seek Opinions on World Policies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials will travel to 15 American cities next year to get opinions about what world trade policy should be in the administration of <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Brunsdale </PERSON>, acting chairwoman of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, said Monday. `` Listening to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> ... the concerns of business executives, labor leaders, politicians and others interested in the impact of tariffs on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industries and consumers ... is crucial if the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> is to offer informed advice to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Trade Representative,'' she said in a statement. At a briefing she added that other barriers to trade as well as tariffs will be discussed at the hearings to be held by the six-member commission. They will begin Jan. 30, 1989, in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> and conclude in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> on April 4. Ms. <PERSON> Brunsdale </PERSON> said she expects that <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Trade Representative, will be writing her in the next few weeks to outline the kind of information he wants. <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> has been the chief <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> representative in the `` <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> round'' of negotiations with nearly 100 countries covering the entire range of international business, not only in manufactured goods but also in farm products and services such as banking and air traffic. A key meeting is due next month in <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> is expected to resign his post afterwards and to be replaced after <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> takes office Jan. 20. The commission is a federal agency that decides whether imports hurt or threaten to hurt particular <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industries, and it recommends what action should be taken. Its advice goes directly to the president. If the <ORGANIZATION> ITC </ORGANIZATION> decides that an imported item has been sold in this country at less than its fair value, or has been subsidized by another government, it can issue an order imposing extra customs duties. It also makes extensive reports to the president and his advisers on trade issues. The commission also will appear at hearings in: <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>, Feb. 1; <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, Feb. 3; <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, Feb. 6; <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, Feb. 13; <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, Feb. 15; <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>. Feb. 17; <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>, Feb. 24; <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, Feb. 27; <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>, March 1; <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo </LOCATION>, March 2; <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, March 13; <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, March 15; and <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>, March 17
