<HEAD>Soviet Military To Make Plumbing Parts to Ease Housing Crunch</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN GILMOUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Part of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s vast defense industry will be turning out plumbing parts for use in a crash program to build more housing, a government official said Monday. <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Batalin </PERSON>, deputy chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministers </ORGANIZATION>, or cabinet, said the military has the facilities for manufacturing the items needed, so defense plants will be put to work turning out the equipment. `` This is happening because available capacities in the defense industry will be reoriented. Rather than producing armaments, they will produce plumbing items,'' <PERSON> Batalin </PERSON> told a news briefing. The involvement of the military in civilian housing programs is just one way Soviets hope to tap various sources for increasing the country's stock of construction equipment and supplies. One city dweller in five lives in a dormitory or communal apartment shared with other families. President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has proclaimed the goal of building enough new housing so each Soviet family can have its own apartment or house by the year 2000. In February, the government announced a plan for citizens to take out large bank loans to build private homes. But even for the enterprising, housing construction often is frustrated by lack of necessary materials. `` The market resources will have to grow,'' said <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boyev </PERSON>, deputy Soviet minister for material and technical supplies. `` We will have to provide the market with the needed materials.'' <PERSON> Boyev </PERSON> said officials understand the shortage of supplies and are trying to speed up production of everything from plumbing parts to linoleum. He said his department made 20,000 square yards of linoleum in 1985 and expects to make 57,000 square yards next year. Individual credits for housing construction are not new, but had been issued on a limited basis until the announcement of the private loan program. Last year, the government provided $ 720 million and in 10 months of this year will have provided $ 2.8 billion, <PERSON> Batalin </PERSON> said. Private construction had been discouraged in official attempts to cut down on pilferage of hard-to-come-by building materials from state enterprises. <PERSON> Batalin </PERSON> said recent changes to permit more economic autonomy in the country's 15 constituent republics will create more of a marketplace atmosphere, alleviating the shortages of materials. N.A. <PERSON> Nazarbayev </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kazakhstan </ORGANIZATION>, one of five Central Asian republics, said the exchange of goods between the republics had at times been arbitrary and unresponsive to needs. For instance, he said, <LOCATION> Kazakhstan </LOCATION> provides the Baltic republic of <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION> with grain and receives footwear in return, when what <LOCATION> Kazakhstan </LOCATION> really needs is timber, which is plentiful in <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Nazarbayev </PERSON> said the self-financing plan will permit the republics to barter or sell products directly for much-needed supplies, adding impetus to the housing construction program.
