<TEXT>
 More than 100 world leaders passed along greetings of peace Monday in the 16th annual World Hello Day organized by two <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> brothers. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Prince <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> and Princess <PERSON> Diana </PERSON> were among the participants this year in the unofficial ritual designed to promote world peace with a series of simple `` hellos.'' `` I guess when you get the heads of states of 100 countries together on anything you have really accomplished something,'' co-founder <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> McCormack </PERSON> said. <PERSON> McCormack </PERSON>, 36, was attending <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in 1973 when he and his brother <PERSON> Brian </PERSON>, 31, started World Hello Day in response to the growing tension in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>. Since then, the annual event that involves greeting at least 10 people in the name of peace has attracted international attention. The brothers received letters of support this year from the leaders of 101 countries, ranging from <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION>. Last week a letter arrived from the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> with a `` warm hello'' from <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, and on Monday the brothers heard from the secretary general of the League of <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Others who have participated in World Hello Day include Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>, <PERSON> Mother </PERSON> <PERSON> Teresa </PERSON>, the late Indian Prime Minister <PERSON> Indira </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>, Bishop <PERSON> Desmond </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON>, Solidarity leader <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, the late Egyptian President <PERSON> Anwar </PERSON> <PERSON> Sadat </PERSON>, Costa Ri