<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A lawyer for confessed <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> hijacker <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> said Monday his client was mentally ill and he asked the court to authorize a psychiatric examination. Also Monday, a former hostage fought back tears as he recalled offering to take his son-in-law's place when the hijackers took several hostages off the plane in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. Chief Judge <PERSON> Heiner </PERSON> <PERSON> Mueckenberger </PERSON> made no immediate ruling on lawyer <PERSON> Hans-Burkhardt </PERSON> <PERSON> Steck </PERSON>'s request for a psychiatrist. <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON>, a Lebanese Shiite Moslem, is charged with murder and air piracy in the hijacking of <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> Flight 847 after it left <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION> for <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> in June 1985. <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> diver <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON> was killed and 39 Americans were held hostage for 17 days. <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> admits he was one of the hijackers but denies killing <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON>. <PERSON> Steck </PERSON> said <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> `` appears to be an adult in many things, but is a child that had been hindered in his development.'' He said <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> was `` mentally disturbed at the time of the hijacking'' but had wanted `` a bloodless hijacking.'' `` The mental and physical damage'' <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> had suffered from fighting in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> `` should have an influence on the sentence.'' While <PERSON> Steck </PERSON> spoke, the mother of the slain diver, <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON>, walked out of the courtroom, apparently fighting back tears. She and her husband, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON>, have followed all 34 sessions since the trial opened July 5. Later, <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> real estate developer <PERSON> Vincente </PERSON> <PERSON> Garza </PERSON> testified that his son-in-law, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Trautmann </PERSON>, was among several hostages taken off the plane at <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> and hidden in the city. `` I thought he could be the first to be shot, and I asked <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> ` do n't take him away, take me.' <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> just pushed me back,'' said <PERSON> Garza </PERSON>, 57, his voice cracking with emotion. Another American testified that she feared the hijackers would harm her because she is Jewish. `` I heard screams and beatings on more than one occasion,'' said <PERSON> Mauri </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwarz </PERSON>, a 36-year-old computer saleswoman. `` I was very afraid because I am Jewish and I did n't know if they knew it.'' Ms. <PERSON> Schwarz </PERSON> said she saw one passenger ask for medical help because he had a heart condition `` but the hijackers refused.'' <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> denied this when asked to comment. `` If anyone had asked me for a doctor, I would have done that,'' he said. The court Monday completed cross-examining Dr. <PERSON> Burton </PERSON> <PERSON> Weber </PERSON>, whose testimony was interrupted Nov. 15 when <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> said he felt ill. <PERSON> Weber </PERSON> said <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> appeared `` less wild and less mean'' than his accomplice, <PERSON> Hassan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ezzeddine </PERSON>, who is a fugitive `` He -LRB- <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> -RRB- was not kind and nice and good, but in my mind he was less frightening,'' <PERSON> Weber </PERSON> said. Under court guidelines to protect witnesses, former hostages do not reveal their hometowns. <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> was arrested at <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> in 1987 after customs officials found liquid explosives in his luggage. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> requested his extradition last year, but the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> German </LOCATION> government turned it down, fearing for the lives of two West Germans held hostage in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. The hostages since have been released. <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON>'s older brother, <PERSON> Abbas </PERSON>, is serving a 13-year prison term in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> in connection with the kidnappings.
