<SECOND>AM-Dangerous Toys,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baby Walkers, Crib Gyms Top This Year's Dangerous Toys List</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Parents who go Christmas shopping for their kids should beware _ there are more dangerous toys than ever before, a consumer group warned Monday. While there are a variety of specific toys which are potentially harmful, entire classes of toys _ baby walkers and crib gyms _ were singled out as dangerous by the <ORGANIZATION> Consumers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> of the Americans for Democratic Action. The 17th annual report of the private, non-profit organization also was critical of the <ORGANIZATION> Consumer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Product </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, the federal agency which oversees toys and other consumer goods. A `` major reason for the abundance of dangerous toys'' is `` the pitiful ineptitude'' of the <ORGANIZATION> CPSC </ORGANIZATION>, the report said. <PERSON> Elaine </PERSON> <PERSON> Tyrrell </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> CPSC </ORGANIZATION>, said the agency would not have any comment because it had n't yet seen the report. But she noted that the <ORGANIZATION> CPSC </ORGANIZATION> soon will issue its own set of Christmas toy guidelines. The report said `` dangerous and potentially dangerous toys are more available than ever this year. Our consumer group was inundated by potentially dangerous toys.'' The report cited <ORGANIZATION> CPSC </ORGANIZATION> statistics which blamed toys for causing 131,000 injuries last year, including 105,000 to kids under 15 years old. Baby walkers can tip over or topple down stairs, making them `` highly dangerous,'' the report said. The <ORGANIZATION> CPSC </ORGANIZATION> received 20,790 injury reports last year from baby walkers, the group noted. Crib gyms have caused 12 deaths and 662 other injuries in the past five years, the report said. `` Warnings are n't enough. Crib gyms need to be designed in the first place without hazards,'' the report said. `` Babies begin to enjoy crib gyms just at the age that parents are advised to remove them. So human nature enters the picture and parents leave the crib gyms a little longer.'' Among the toys cited by the <ORGANIZATION> ADA </ORGANIZATION> panel as potentially dangerous: _ Inflatable sleds, some of which throw up snow that could blind the driver _ Flammable items, including stuffed animals _ Household-type toys urging children to imitate adults in a dangerous fashion The report cited an electric oven which could burn a kid and a toy iron that has a realistic-looking plug that could send children to the nearest electrical outlet. _ Items which could be dangerous if broken One example cited was a toy doctor's kit which included realistic-looking plastic instruments that could break when a child puts them up to his face, throat, ears or eyes. _ Items dangerous for babies, including rattles that do n't meet specified width requirements A baby could choke on that rattle, the report said. _ Toys with inadequate or misleading age labels In some instances, manufacturers label a product containing small parts as `` for ages over 3,'' but it still appeals to younger kids. Parents who go toy shopping in the next month should keep several things in mind, the report noted, including: _ Safety Look for sharp edges, small parts, projectiles and potential danger if the toy breaks. Toys with fabric in them should say the material is flame retardant or flame resistant. Painted toys should be non-toxic. _ Look at the toy, not the box Examine the contents to make sure it is the same as what's pictured outside. _ Consider the toy's play value Will the child enjoy it more than once or be bored after 15 minutes? _ Batteries Few toys include batteries. _ Save sales receipts Some stores will match the price of their competition. _ Read the directions Avoid toys with instructions that are too complicated. _ Check newspaper ads Popular toys may go on sale just before Christmas and be more readily available late in the season. _ Consider the child's age Good toys should not require constant supervision to ensure safety or correct use. _ Avoid `` hot'' items They might be cheaper next year, and ads overglamorize them.
