<HEAD>Reagan Library Faced Ideological, Environmental Pitfalls</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Reagan Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SIMI VALLEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sponsors of a library documenting the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> presidency have had to steer around a variety of pitfalls, from liberal <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> professors to a rare six-inch sunflower. Groundbreaking here Monday for the <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> Presidential Library was made possible by a compromise with environmentalists that protects the sunflower and two other rare plants. Before that, the <ORGANIZATION> Ronald </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reagan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> had to overcome concerns that the project would detract from a section of rolling coastal mountain range set aside by local planners as a protected area. And all that came after the foundation abandoned its original plans to construct the library on a 20-acre Northern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> site at <LOCATION> Stanford </LOCATION> in conjunction with a proposed policy center. Neighbors of the university had complained about expected tourist traffic, while liberal professors did n't want the campus used to enshrine the memory of a conservative champion. <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION>'s trustees split the library from the proposed policy center in 1984, but planning for the library continued into 1987, up to the point that blueprints were unveiled with fanfare in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. In April 1987, the foundation canceled its <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> plans, publicly citing the separation three years earlier of the library from the policy center. In the ensuing months, a number of potential sites in <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> were rumored to be under consideration, including the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION>, Riverside and the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANI