<HEAD>Westerners Don't Hear Eastern Results Until Polls Close</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Canada, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, the world's second-largest country sprawling across six time zones, forbids broadcasters from spreading election results while polls remain open. That means election coverage starts at 8 p.m. local time in each zone as the polls close, unlike the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> system where the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> coast receives network coverage while voting continues. `` We've got six time zones; that's why we've got to be very cautious,'' said <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Mackay </PERSON> of the federal <ORGANIZATION> Elections </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canada </ORGANIZATION> agency. `` Of course, it's very difficult today in the age of comunications to limit it _ but it's still done.'' <PERSON> Mackay </PERSON> said in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> Ottawa </LOCATION> that the law prohibits broadcasters from talking about election results while polls remain open in any particular time zone. `` It's still possible to phone somebody in the East and say, ` What's going on?''' <PERSON> Bazay </PERSON> said. The majority of <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s population lives in <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION>, which are on Eastern Standard Time. Those two provinces account for 10.7 million of the 17.5 million voters registered for Monday's election and 174 of the 295 seats in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commons </ORGANIZATION> That leads to complaints from those who live farther west, especially <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, which has 32 seats, where polls close three hours later. `` It's very simple,'' <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Bazay </PERSON>, executive producer of the public Canadian <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s network news, said when asked to explain the system. `` We do it every day as a matter of course. Our national news basically has five editions.'' Election programming for <LOCATION> Newfoundland </LOCATION>, where polls close at 6:30 p.m. EST, can start in the central studio in <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> and be broadcast regionally. The <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> of <LOCATION> Nova </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Scotia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brunswick </LOCATION> and Prince <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Island </PERSON> is added an hour later, then <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION>. `` We have a network. We can put the entire national network together, or parts of it together,'' <PERSON> Bazay </PERSON> said. `` As the polls close across the country, we simply put on election coverage. ... It's not complicated at all.'' The private Canadian TV network also was planning coverage starting at 8 p.m. local time. Global was not starting its coverage until about 10:15 p.m., after the conclusion of a <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hockey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> game between <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION>. Satellite and cable television are increasingly available to Canadian households. <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Pontbriand </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Canadian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, said it was the responsibility of each satellite and cable licensee to comply with the election law.
