<TEXT>
 Women will have 50 percent more restrooms than men in new public buildings in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, as officialdom tries to compensate for the different lengths of time the sexes spend in the bathroom. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Rollison </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Delegates </ORGANIZATION> proposed the `` potty parity'' revision to the state building code after a study showed that women take longer in restrooms and are forced to wait in lines to use the facilities at sporting events and theaters. The study said women take more time because they frequently are accompanied by small children and because they wear more clothes than men. The State Housing and <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> voted Saturday to increase the required number of women's restrooms in public places by 50 percent, effective March 1. The provision will apply only to new construction of large public gathering places such as sports arenas and movie theaters. Men's and women's restrooms are currently required to be built in an even ratio. `` I'm pleased they made the change,'' <PERSON> Rollison </PERSON> said. `` I think this will open some new doors for women in the commonwealth.''
