<HEAD>Company Uses Austin, San Antonio As Test Sites For No-Smoking
Policy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A computer chip maker has adopted a strict no-smoking policy in its <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> plants in a policy shift that some predict will sweep the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> semiconductor industry. The new rules, which take effect Jan. 2, apply to all <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> employees of <ORGANIZATION> Advanced </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Micro </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Devices </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> _ 2,200 in <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION> and 900 in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION>. `` It's kind of a pilot project in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Frink </PERSON>, a local spokesman for the California-based company. The company plans to remove ash trays and cigarette machines and has encouraged workers to join smoking cessation classes, designed by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>. Employees previously were allowed to smoke in designated areas, although never in the `` clean rooms'' where delicate computer chips are made. <PERSON> Frink </PERSON> said the company revised its smoking policy to eliminate a potential source of chip-destroying contaminants. A speck of dust or smoke particle can block part of a microscopic circuit and ruin a chip. He said it also responds to recent evidence linking nonsmokers' health hazards to second-hand smoke The company chose <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> for the experiment because its operations are smaller here than in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Frink </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Austin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American-Statesman </ORGANIZATION>. In addition, chips made in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> are among its most sensitive. Other chipmakers predicted more companies would follow suit. <PERSON> Stan </PERSON> <PERSON> Victor </PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Instruments </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, said the company discourages smoking but has not yet gone as far as Advanced Micro Devices. <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Instruments </ORGANIZATION> offers smoking cessation classes to employees and their spouses, <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> said, and asks clean room employees who smoke during breaks to rinse their mouths with water and wait at least five minutes before re-entering the chip-making area. <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyman </PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said the company has banned smoking in some of its newer manufacturing buildings. But it allows designated smoking areas in compliance with an <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION> ordinance. The manager of contamination engineering for <ORGANIZATION> Sematech </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> Dillenbeck </PERSON>, said Advanced Micro Devices' policy likely will spread through the industry. `` There is a trend in that direction,'' <PERSON> Dillenbeck </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Dillenbeck </PERSON> said technical journals have indicated smoke can linger in the mouth and lungs, as well as cling to clothes and hair, as long as two hours after smoking. As a result, he said, smokers in the clean room may generate as many as 10 times more particles than non-smokers.
