<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s three holdover Cabinet appointees wo n't face a second round of <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> confirmation hearings thanks to a ruling 60 years ago on then-Treasury Secretary <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Mellon </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> officials said Monday. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has asked Attorney General <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>, Education Secretary <PERSON> Lauro </PERSON> <PERSON> Cavazos </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> to stay in their jobs in his new administration. All three men have joined the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration since August, and all experienced no problems being confirmed by a majority of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Davidson </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s legal counsel, said they would n't have to undergo the confirmation process next year _ unless <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> wanted them to If he did, the men would formally resign, only to be re-nominated by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. That wo n't happen, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s transition aides said. `` We're following the precedent that we think was wisely ... followed by <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Buren </PERSON>, who did not submit his nominees that were held over for reconfirmation,'' said <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON>, co-director of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s transition office. Since <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON>'s time there have been cases of Cabinet appointees remaining in office over the span of more than one president, according to <PERSON> Davidson </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s legal counsel. For example, Secretary of State <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Pickering </PERSON> served both <LOCATION>