<HEAD>States Go To Court With EPA Again Over Acid Rain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nine states filed a new lawsuit Monday against the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> in their 5-year legal effort to force the agency to order new acid rain controls in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>. The states, joined by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Audubon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>, asked the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> to review <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s refusal to act on their petition seeking those controls. That petition called on <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> to publish for public comment the determination of the <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> administration's <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> chief that sulfur dioxide emissions from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> were harming <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. Such a publication is the first step in drafting a regulation. The Canadian province of <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION> and two environmental organizations filed a similar lawsuit in the same court on Nov. 1. A few days before leaving office in January 1981, <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> Administrator <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Costle </PERSON> wrote Secretary of State <PERSON> Edmund </PERSON> <PERSON> Muskie </PERSON> that these emissions were harming <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> by being transformed in the atmosphere into sulfuric acid, which falls as acid rain in eastern <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. Many of these sulfur dioxide emissions originate in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> in power plant and factory smokestacks. Once such a determination is made, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> law requires <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> to order affected states to revise their air pollution control plans to eliminate the offending emissions. But the appeals court, in a decision upheld by the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, ruled earlier that a letter to the secretary of state was not formal enough, and any such determination had to be made in formal proceedings leading to a regulation. <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION>, the nine states and various environmental groups all petitioned for such formal proceedings, but <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> in October said it would not act on those petitions because it still did not know enough to tell states in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> how to revise their air pollution control measures. Environmentalists say acid rain has made hundreds of lakes in the <LOCATION> Adirondack </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> State </LOCATION> unlivable for fish. <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> says 14,000 lakes in the eastern half of that country have been damaged. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Wooley </PERSON>, an assistant attorney general of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION>, one of the plaintiff states, said in <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, the states are entitled to sue because they are harmed by the same pollutant harming <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. He said he has asked that his lawsuit be consolidated with <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION>'s. In addition to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the plaintiff states are the six <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> states, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>.
