<HEAD>Signup for Wheat, Feed Grain, Cotton Programs Announced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Farmers who want to participate in the government's 1989 programs for wheat, feed grain and upland cotton can sign up Dec. 19 through April 14 at county offices, <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> announced Monday. The signup dates for 1989 rice and extra-long staple cotton programs will be announced later, he said. Farmers also will be able to `` declare their intentions'' from Dec. 19 through Feb. 3 to plant 10 percent to 25 percent of each program crop's permitted acreage to soybeans or sunflowers and still protect the acreage base history for the program crops, <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> said. In addition, the 1989 program allows a portion of a farm's acreage base to be used for oats, with certain stipulations affecting soybeans During the signup, wheat and feed grains producers may request 40 percent and upland cotton and rice producers 30 percent of their estimated 1989 deficiency payments. These preliminary payments will be in cash. Deficiency payments are direct subsidies made to farmers to help bridge the gap between lower market prices and `` target'' prices set for each commodity. For wheat and feed grains, farmers will be able to participate in an optional acreage `` diversion'' or land-idling program called 0-92. Under it, a farmer can devote all or part of his crop's permitted acreage to soil-conserving uses and get deficiency payments on up to 92 percent of the land <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> and upland cotton farmers will be able to participate in a 50-92 version.
