<HEAD>Bush Advised to Use New Powers on World Trade</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President-elect <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> should make vigorous use of new powers that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has given the president to get satisfaction from other countries in trade disputes, a congressional investigative agency said Monday. In one of a series of reports on important issues for the transition to the new presidency, the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> said it has found many instances when a follow-up was needed to get the benefits of an international trade agreement. It added that delaying tactics and slow dispute settlements have often frustrated efforts to get satisfaction, but the new Trade Act strengthens the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> hand. `` Failure to gain timely satisfaction can now trigger a unilateral <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> response,'' the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> report said. `` The new administration should show strong resolve to vigorously use these new powers.'' One provision of the trade law <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> signed in August permits him to specify what he considers high-priority unfair trade practices and to start action toward retaliation while trying to get a settlement by negotiation. Another provision permits him to rule that a country denying internationally recognized rights to labor can be considered as engaging in an unfair trade practice, and to retaliate against its trade. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> complained of defects in efforts to promote exports. It said the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has chosen questionable trade promotion events and has been active in countries with little or no potential for buying more <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> goods. It did not specify the nations. It characterized as `` largely symbolic'' the controls put on exports to further foreign policy objectives, as distinct from controls that have security objectives. `` When these controls are symbolic, they do not prevent the targeted country from getting the controlled products from other countries,'' the report said. `` Instead their costs are borne by American businesses in the form of export sales lost to firms in other countries.'' The report did not specify either the countries targeted by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> controls or their suppliers. One nation to which exports are controlled for foreign policy reasons is <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, where Japanese and West European suppliers have replaced many exports that can now no longer be shipped by Americans.
