<HEAD>Bush Urged To Name Only Experienced People to Top Defense Jobs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President-elect <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> should only appoint civilians to the top Pentagon jobs if they have a substantial background in national security issues, the leaders of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. `` Strong defense leadership will be needed during the next four years,'' said <PERSON> Sens </PERSON>. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>, D-Ga., and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Warner </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Va </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> chairs the committee and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> is the ranking In a letter sent before the election to both <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Democratic candidate <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, the two senators outlined what they said should be some general qualification standards for top-level civilian appointments to the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. The letter was released Monday. There was no reply from <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who has n't yet named any members of his national security team. Former Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Tower </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> is considered to be a leading candidate to become secretary of defense. <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> said they did n't want to spell out specific qualifications for each civilian appointment. The <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> will oversee top-level appointments requiring <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> confirmation. The two senators said criteria should include integrity, a commitment to public service and ability to get along with other top-level <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> officials. In addition, there should be `` substantial experience and expertise,'' they said, because `` there is no time for ` on-the-job' training in the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION>. Nominees also `` should have a substantial understanding of national security policy and international security affairs,'' the senators said.
