<HEAD>Ethnic Albanians Defy Threats of Crackdown, Protest</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-6 UPDATE with bad weather conditions, second rally
in Slovenia. PICKS up 5th pvs, `The two ...' SUBS 11th pvs `Local
Communist Party ...' to CORRECT to Imsa, sted of Isma. Minor editing
to TRIM</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SLOBODAN LEKIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 At least 7,000 ethnic Albanians angered by the ouster of two leaders defied threats of a crackdown and took to the streets in heavy rain Monday, extending a wave of ethnic protest for a fifth straight day. The demonstrators marched about 40 miles to <LOCATION> Pristina </LOCATION>, capital of the restive southern province of <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>. In the northern republic of <LOCATION> Slovenia </LOCATION>, about 13,000 people braved a snowstorm Monday to press for more democracy. The two protests were not related. The Slovenians called for a referendum on controversial constitutional changes and for acquittal of four men sentenced to jail for making public a classified military document. A rally in Revolution Square in <LOCATION> Ljubljana </LOCATION>, the Slovenian capital, drew 10,000 people and another rally in <LOCATION> Celje </LOCATION>, 42 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Ljubljana </LOCATION>, drew 3,000. Slovenian courts acted at the last minute Monday to postpone the scheduled jailing of the three journalists and one army officer, whose sentencing last summer led to protests and petitions in the most liberal of <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s six republics. <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> protesters were angered by the resignations Thursday of <PERSON> Azem </PERSON> <PERSON> Vlasi </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kacusa </PERSON> <PERSON> Jasari </PERSON>, both ethnic <PERSON> Albanian </PERSON> members of the province's 13-member ruling Politburo. The two stepped down under pressure from <ORGANIZATION> Serbian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Slobodan </PERSON> <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON>, who wants greater control over <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> for its republic, <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION>. He has demanded changes in the 1974 constitution that gave <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> broad autonomy. Provincial party leaders have promised to review the resignations of the two ethnic Albanians later this week. In a speech Monday in <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON> reiterated his demand for the constitutional changes he says are needed to protect <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>'s Serb minority from harassment by ethnic Albanians. He made no reference to the weekend protests in <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> by up to 100,000 ethnic Albanians. At Monday's protest in a <LOCATION> Pristina </LOCATION> sports hall, a crowd of about 7,000, mostly workers who trudged 40 miles from the town of <LOCATION> Orohovac </LOCATION>, dispersed after a Serbian factory worker defied <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON> and backed the ethnic Albanians. The worker, <PERSON> Ruzica </PERSON> <PERSON> Imsa </PERSON>, was cheered wildly as she spoke out against the constitutional reforms pressed by many of her fellow Serbs. `` The working class will not allow itself to be pushed around,'' she said. `` We will not let anyone impose constitutional changes the people do not want.'' Local Communist Party leaders were jeered and whistled when they tried to get the crowd to return home. They then persuaded <ORGANIZATION> Imsa </ORGANIZATION> to return to the microphone, and her calm appeal succeeded in dispersing the crowd. Later, another crowd of about 2,000 people arrived from the town of <LOCATION> Klina </LOCATION>, some 40 miles north of <LOCATION> Pristina </LOCATION>. Officials had warned of a crackdown if protesters took to the streets. At an earlier gathering at <ORGANIZATION> Pristina </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, acting provincial party head <PERSON> Remzi </PERSON> <PERSON> Koljgeci </PERSON> told students `` unspecified measures'' would go into force if more protests occurred. Under a package of constitutional amendments due to be passed by each republic by next week, <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON> wants to restore Serbian control over <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>'s judiciary, education and policing. The amendments are designed to simplify the complex federal constitution and give the legal framework to introduce market-oriented economic reform. Most of <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON>'s address dwelt on the need for economic change and strongly attacked bureaucrats for opposing it. Communist leaders in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s other five republics see <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON>'s campaign as a drive to increase the influence of <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION>, the largest republic, on the Yugoslav federation. But <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON> claims the changes would only put <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION> on an equal footing with other republics, which have no administrative provinces like <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Vojvodina </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Slovenia </LOCATION>, the proposed reforms have run into opposition from intellectuals who fear greater central control of the republic's relatively liberal judiciary The rally in <LOCATION> Ljubljana </LOCATION> pressed demands for a referendum on the reforms, which intellectuals believe would be strongly opposed in <LOCATION> Slovenia </LOCATION>.
