<HEAD>Oil Workers End Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tens of thousands of oil workers returned to work Monday, ending a 10-day strike that caused widespread shortages of cooking gas and heating oil. Unions meeting Sunday and Monday voted to accept a government offer of wage increases, said <PERSON> Lucio </PERSON> <PERSON> Pimentel </PERSON>, spokesman for the Petrobras state oil monopoly. The strike by more than 50,000 petroleum workers paralyzed the nation's 11 refineries. In emergency bargaining during the weekend, the government offered strikers a 15 percent cost-of-living raise and a 4 percent raise tied to productivity. Oil workers earn about $ 300 a month, good pay by Brazilian standards. <ORGANIZATION> Petrobras </ORGANIZATION> also agreed not to punish strikers and to deduct only four days' pay from their checks. Strike leaders urged unions to accept the offer, although it fell short of the 26.6 percent raise they demanded. The government had suspended the cost-of-living raise last year when it decreed a 90-day price freeze. Officials said granting the raise would create more inflation, now at an annual rate of more than 1,000 percent. `` It was a great political victory, although economically it did n't attain what we wanted,'' <PERSON> Mauro </PERSON> <PERSON> Costa </PERSON> of the national strike command said in <LOCATION> Brasilia </LOCATION>. During the strike, the government was forced to import emergency shipments of diesel fuel, cooking gas and kerosene when stocks threatened to run out completely. Gas rationing was imposed in some parts of the country. <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> has suffered a recent wave of strikes caused by a sputtering economy under President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON>. The strikers have included national park employees, doctors and nurses at government-run clinics, electricity workers, subway personnel, steelworkers and federal employees in at least 17 of 26 ministries.
