<HEAD>Reagan Attends Ground-Breaking for Library</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 7th graf pvs, bgng: ``The journey...'' to remove
reference to prepared remarks; SUBS 14th graf pvs, bgng: ``The
library...'' with 4 grafs to add details; picks up 15th graf pvs,
bgng: ``The building...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIMI VALLEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> on Monday helped break ground for the library that will house his <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> papers, saying he hoped historians and scholars would `` judge our efforts well.'' `` This is a most humbling moment for me,'' said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, who will relinquish the presidency to <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in 60 days. `` The story that will be told inside the walls that are yet to be built here is the story not only of a presidency, but of a movement.'' The president and his wife <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> flew from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> to take part in the ceremonies for the <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> Presidential Library. The 153,000-square-foot, Spanish-style facility will be built on a 100-acre site about 45 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Reagans </ORGANIZATION> gave final approval to the site last summer, after the president viewed the sweeping, hilly area from a helicopter following a ground inspection by the first lady. The selection of the <LOCATION> Simi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> site, about 70 miles southeast of the <ORGANIZATION> Reagans </ORGANIZATION>' ranch in <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Barbara </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, came after planners of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> library were thwarted in an attempt to build it at <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Palo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alto </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif </LOCATION>. Appearing at the ceremony at the outset of a six-day Thanksgiving vacation at his ranch in the <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ynez </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> talked reflectively of his eight years as president. `` The journey has not been just my own,'' he said. `` It seems I have been guided by a force much larger than myself, a force made up of ideas and beliefs about what this country is and what it could be.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> takes credit for a resurgence of conservatism in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, and much of the 1988 campaign rhetoric during the Republican primary season was about what man could best carry on the `` <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> revolution.'' This sea-change was based on a fiscal policy at home aimed at stimulating economic growth through tax cuts and deregulation of business, and a resurgence of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> international influence brought about principally by a major military buildup, projections of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> power in the Third World and warming, if unsteady, relations with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. `` What this library will house is the record of ideas and policies that have undergirded our accomplishments,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. `` There will be much to study here, much to discuss, much to mull over.'' `` This library will allow scholars of the future to cast their own judgments on these years, and I would not presume to predict the result of their researches,'' he said. `` But I have to believe that scholars of good will, upon examining the historical record that will be contained herein, will judge our efforts well.'' `` But as for us, at present we can only say this: We have done our best and we pray that it has been enough.'' The land for the library was donated by a <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> development company, <PERSON> Blakeley-Schwartz </PERSON>. The selection sparked opposition by environmentalists initially because the site impinged on a greenbelt area protected from large-scale development by a decade-old, non-binding agreement among <LOCATION> Simi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Moorpark </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Thousand </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Oaks </LOCATION>. The $ 45 million library will be constructed with donations to the private <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> library foundation. It will sit in an area of rolling hills covered with brush, beavertail cactus and wildflowers. Former Attorney General <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> French </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> told the audience that over 100,000 people have contributed toward the library's cost, but he did not say how much of the money has been raised. Arrayed on the platform next to the <ORGANIZATION> Reagans </ORGANIZATION> were several members of the board of trustees of the presidential library foundation, including former Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>, former National Security Adviser and <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>, former domestic policy adviser <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, and Energy Secretary <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Herrington </PERSON>. After his brief speech, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> walked about 30 feet up a knoll, and he and his wife, each wielding stainless steel shovels that glistened in the bright sun, turned the first shovelsful of dirt as more than 250 people applauded. The building will include underground storage, a museum and research materials depicting the administration and historical events during the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> years. As the curtain draws on the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> presidency, the first couple seems prepared for the transition back to private life. they will move into a luxurious home in the Bel Air section of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> in January _ an estate that they will lease from friends who acquired the property in their behalf. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has said he plans to lecture often `` on the mashed potato circuit'' and Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has said she will remain active in the campaign against drug abuse. While in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> this week, aides said, the president will act on various pieces of legislation passed by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in its waning days last month. Following their usual pattern, the <ORGANIZATION> Reagans </ORGANIZATION> also will go horseback riding, and the president will attend to ranch chores. After their return to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> on Sunday, they will have a busy schedule of parties and other social commitments in their final weeks in the capital.
