olicy objectives, as distinct from controls which have security objectives. `` When these controls are symbolic, they do not prevent the targeted country from getting the controlled products from other countries,'' the report said. `` Instead their costs are borne by American businesses in the form of export sales lost to firms in other countries.'' The report did not specify either the countries targeted by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> controls, or their suppliers. One country where <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exports are controlled because of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> foreign policy is <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, where Japanese and west European suppliers have replaced many exports that can now no longer be shppied by Americans.
