<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> is ready to demand a worldwide end to colonialism and to condemn <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s rule of <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. The assembly appears certain to approve a resolution Tuesday declaring the 1990s to be the International Decade for the Eradication of Colonialism. It also will probably pass a resolution denouncing <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s control of <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, or <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>. Last year, a resolution calling for Namibian independence passed 131-2, with seven abstentions. Only the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> voted against it. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> was stripped of its voting rights in the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> in 1974. When the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> was established in 1945, 750 million people lived without self-government in territories dependent on colonial powers. By 1985, fewer than 3 million people still lived in such territories. Talks are under way to grant independence to <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>'s 1.5 million residents and <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION>'s 117,000. A tentative accord reached last week among <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> paves the way for <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> to grant independence to <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, with the one-year transition possibly beginning early next year. <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> would remove its troops from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, where it is supporting the Marxist go