<HEAD>Gunman Kills Officer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A gunman killed a police officer and wounded another Monday night in a town north of <LOCATION> Belfast </LOCATION>, then fled on a motorcycle, police said. The slain officer, identified as 50-year-old <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Monteith </PERSON>, was filling in for a colleague on sick leave when he was shot in <LOCATION> Castlederg </LOCATION>, 60 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Belfast </LOCATION> and close to the border with the <LOCATION> Irish </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION>, police said. The second officer, identified only as <PERSON> Monteith </PERSON>'s nephew, was grazed in the head by a bullet, they said. The shooting took place shortly before the officers were to have closed security barriers to protect the town at night from <ORGANIZATION> Irish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> bomb attacks. The <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Londonderry </LOCATION> said it had a telephone call claiming <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> responsibility for the attack. The victim was the sixth policeman killed this year and the 257th since the mostly Roman Catholic <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> began its violent struggle in 1969 to end British rule in the predominately <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION> province.
