<SECOND>PM-AP Arts: The Feelies, ADV 23,0909</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv 23</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed PMs, Nov 23 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Staying In Touch With the Feelies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Staying in touch is what the <ORGANIZATION> Feelies </ORGANIZATION> are all about. With their audience. And with their music. `` I'd rather appeal to 500 people for the right reasons than 5,000 for the wrong reasons. It's really what you mean to people,'' group member <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> <PERSON> Mercer </PERSON> said. As for their music, <PERSON> Mercer </PERSON> said, `` We're reducing it to its basic element. Pure energy and spirit. No intellect involved at all, really. `` You do n't want to make it seem that it's really being thought about. You do n't write a song about people being fascinated, it just sort of comes out of you. No preconceived ideas.'' On their third album, `` Only Life,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Feelies </ORGANIZATION> stick to the same unfettered approach. The lyrics are terse, like telegrams; every word counts. The singing is deliberately flat, stripped of all emotion and irony. The listener is left to wonder if such words as, `` Nothing matters and what if it did,'' are to be taken at face value or a criticism of that attitude. `` All of our songs are open to interpretation,'' <PERSON> Mercer </PERSON> said. `` I'd much prefer that to saying what the song's about. I think you failed in a way if you have to say what a song's about. It really takes away something from the song.'' The arrangements keep to the basic rock' n' roll combination of drums, bass and guitars. <PERSON> Mercer </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Feelies </ORGANIZATION> were attracted to the Stooges, the Modern Lovers and the MC5 _ groups more interested in emotion than fancy chord structures. `` It was a combination. One, being that they're pretty simple bands. They gave you the feeling you did n't have to take years of music lessons, did n't have to buy really expensive equipment. You could make music on a personal level. Another thing, they were cult bands. Nobody else knew about them.'' <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Million </PERSON>, who co-writes the <ORGANIZATION> Feelies </ORGANIZATION>' songs with <PERSON> Mercer </PERSON>, liked the spontaneous feel of those groups. `` The music had a lot of energy,'' he said. `` The Stooges sounded like the guitar player just got a fender, a fuzz box and an amplifier for <PERSON> Christman </PERSON> and just recorded the album two weeks later.'' But that changed in the 70s. `` Then it got away from that. Bands like <PERSON> Emerson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Lake </PERSON> and <PERSON> Palmer </PERSON> and Yes, just the opposite really.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Feelies </ORGANIZATION> were high school students in <LOCATION> Haledon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, when the group was formed in 1976. The original lineup consisted of <PERSON> Mercer </PERSON> and Million on guitars, <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Weckerman </PERSON> on drums and percussion and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> on bass. They made their debut at <ORGANIZATION> Manchester </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Haledon </LOCATION> the following year, not too successfully, Million remembered. `` The audience was n't getting into what we were doing. Between breaks, they asked us if they could use the instruments and play stuff the audience actually wanted to hear. Then we started playing <ORGANIZATION> CBGB </ORGANIZATION>'s and <PERSON> Max </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>.'' And then the <ORGANIZATION> Feelies </ORGANIZATION> caught on. In 1978, they were called `` The Best Underground Band in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'' in a Village Voice cover story. `` Our audience went from about 12 to 600 people,'' Million recalled. It seemed like a perfect fit when the <ORGANIZATION> Feelies </ORGANIZATION> signed with <ORGANIZATION> Stiff </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Records </ORGANIZATION> and released their debut album, `` Crazy Rhythms,'' in 1980. Here was the `` Best Underground Band'' and the ultimate new wave record label, the home of <PERSON> Elvis </PERSON> <PERSON> Costello </PERSON>, <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> and <PERSON> Nick </PERSON> <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON>. The Feelies found out, however, that Stiff had the same priority as the major record companies: the bottom line. `` They lectured us on how to write a hit single. It was like a scene out of a movie,'' <PERSON> Mercer </PERSON> said. There were no hit singles, and despite excellent reviews, `` Crazy Rhythms'' was a commercial failure and the <ORGANIZATION> Feelies </ORGANIZATION> disbanded in 1981. Not because they wanted to, <PERSON> Mercer </PERSON> noted. `` We did n't anticipate not playing for that long. The gigs got further and further apart. We were n't thinking in turns of a finality. We tend to go where things lead. We got involved in doing different things. Not wanting to get involved with another bad experience.'' But the Feelies were not forgotten. Film director <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Demme </PERSON> had seen the band play at the Whiskey A Go Go in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and suggested that <PERSON> Mercer </PERSON> and Million write the soundtrack for <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Seidelman </PERSON>'s `` Smithereens,'' released in 1982. `` He was a fan of the band. We kept in touch,'' Million said. The <ORGANIZATION> Feelies </ORGANIZATION> regrouped in 1983 with <PERSON> Brenda </PERSON> <PERSON> Sauter </PERSON> on bass, <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Demeski </PERSON> on drums and Weckerman moving to percussion. In 1986, they released `` The Good Earth'' on <ORGANIZATION> Coyote </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Records </ORGANIZATION>. The same year, the <ORGANIZATION> Feelies </ORGANIZATION> appeared in <PERSON> Demme </PERSON>'s hit film, `` Something Wild,'' performing a cover of the <ORGANIZATION> Monkees </ORGANIZATION>' `` I'm a Believer'' at a high school reunion. `` It was fun, a lot of hard work, but primarily fun. They made us comfortable,'' <PERSON> Mercer </PERSON> said. But the <ORGANIZATION> Feelies </ORGANIZATION> are not looking to be a ` fun' band. They're not interested in being ` fashionable.' They seek connection with their fans through music. `` The people there are just there for the music. It's not like going to the disco and getting dressed and making the scene,'' <PERSON> Mercer </PERSON> said. Added Million: `` There is n't a scene to make.''
</TEXT>
