<NOTE>$Adv30</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed AMs, Nov. 30, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Minor Parties Seek Inroads in Congress in Venezuela's Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARRIE FIGDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With little hope of winning the presidency, <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>'s minor political parties are seeking to make inroads in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in national elections Dec. 4. They are counting on a major defection from the nation's two main parties. The small parties acknowledge that their 23 presidential candidates _ including a handful of leftists, a witchdoctor, some retired military officers, and a former <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> president _ do n't have a chance in the presidential balloting. But they say widespread voter discontent with the government's <ORGANIZATION> Accion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratica </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- AD -RRB- and the main opposition party, Copei, will be shown in split-ticket voting that could yield a <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> of 182 deputies and 44 senators with no single party in control It would mean a major change in recent Venezuelan voting patterns with longer-term effects as the nation slowly decentralizes its political system, they said. `` People are not happy with AD or Copei but they recognize their candidates have the best chance to win the presidency. But their true electoral preference will be shown in the congressional vote,'' said <PERSON> Freddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Munoz </PERSON>, secretary general of Movement to Socialism -LRB- MAS -RRB-, <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>'s third largest electoral force. Most political analysts agree small parties, the larger of which are left of center, are likely to post gains in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. They note that voters associate the country's economic slump, about to enter its eighth year, with center-right <ORGANIZATION> Copei </ORGANIZATION> and center-left AD. The crisis, caused by low oil prices, began under a <ORGANIZATION> Copei </ORGANIZATION> administration and has continued under current AD administration of President <PERSON> Jaime </PERSON> <PERSON> Lusinchi </PERSON>. Polls indicate that while over 75 percent of the electorate express a preference for either AD's frontrunning candidate <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Andres </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> or Copei's <PERSON> Eduardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON>, only half the eligible voters have decided to vote for one of the two parties' congressional slates The disaffection has been exacerbated by unexciting campaigns. AD politicians bemoan the `` triumphalism'' of the party's candidates, who have depended on <PERSON> Perez </PERSON>'s popularity to sweep them into office rather than campaigning for themselves. MAS, on the other hand, adopted a campaign strategy that de-emphasized the campaign of its presidential candidate, former guerrilla <PERSON> Teodoro </PERSON> <PERSON> Petkoff </PERSON>, in favor of its congressional candidates. The ticket-splitting would be a major change from recent Venezuelan voting patterns. In the six elections since 1958, AD and <ORGANIZATION> Copei </ORGANIZATION> alternated in the presidency. Since 1973 the two parties combined have garnered not less than 88 percent of the presidential vote. Minor parties had just 27 seats in the last 200-member House of Deputies, including 10 from MAS. AD had 113 seats and <ORGANIZATION> Copei </ORGANIZATION> 60 _ and some of the small parties ally themselves with AD or Copei. But even if MAS gets around 15 percent of the congressional vote, as some analysts predict, it likely would have little impact on the direction of Venezuelan politics in the short term. With <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>'s overwhelmingly strong executive branch, congressional action is normally limited to making minor adjustments to presidential initiatives. But ticket-splitting could mean a revival of MAS and the ability of small national or regional parties to survive until the presidential election in 1993. Their survival takes on more significance as the big parties reluctantly allow some decentralization of power to take place.
</TEXT>
