<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Dec. 4
^From AP Newsfeatures</NOTE>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 4 b&amp;w
photos.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 EDITOR'S NOTE _ For most of the 70 years since the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> came into being, Soviet history was tailored and falsified to suit the rulers in the Kremlin and the party dogmatists. In today's freer atmosphere, long suppressed truths are allowed to emerge, and the nation is trying hard to come to grips with them.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>

</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In a cool pine glade north of the <LOCATION> Byelorussian </LOCATION> capital of <LOCATION> Minsk </LOCATION> where Soviet families used to come to picnic, stroll or play chess, two schoolboys made a grisly discovery. Digging around in the Kuropaty forest during their May Day holiday last spring, the boys unearthed some human skeletons that started a grim search for historical truth. Since then, archaeologists have made wholescale excavations, and researchers now estimate that more than 100,000 people were shot and buried in mass graves there during the political purges of the late 1930s. In the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, the past never lies far beneath the surface. History is an abiding obsession here. For the Soviet nation, whose 70-year existence fits into a single human lifespan, the past surges up again and again to influence the present. In the more open atmosphere permitted by President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s policy of glasnost, Soviets are trying to come to grips with their nation's often dark, troubling and contradictory legacy _ and use it to map a course for the future. `` People write heatedly and passionately about the events of 50 years ago as if they were writing about today's problems,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said this year. `` There is nothing surprising about this. They are talking about the most important thing for us ... about how it could happen that, along with the heroic achievements of the people, crimes against them became possible.'' World War II is re-fought several times a week on state-run television, in movies and documentaries. Rainy fall days barely thin the throngs outside the red brick gates of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s Novodevichy Cemetery, where Soviets come to see the tombs of departed Kremlin leaders who once fixed the course of their lives. History is never far behind the headlines: _ Armenians waging a long, noisy campaign to annex the <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> region of neighboring <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> are contesting a <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> government decision made in 1923 that awarded the predominantly Armenian region to <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>. _ In the three <LOCATION> Baltic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> republics </LOCATION>, mass movements arise to demand greater autonomy from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. Some Estonians, Latvians and Lithuanians even seek total independence. Demonstrations are triggered by each anniversary of the 1939 Hitler-Stalin pact that awarded control of the states, then sovereign nations, to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, which absorbed them. _ <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, embarked on a bold course to revitalize the nation's economy, trim its bureaucracy and get the citizenry more involved in decision-making, rarely speaks publicly without citing the stagnation of <PERSON> Leonid </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON>'s rule and the harsh administrative grip imposed by dictator <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> In the atmosphere of freer inquiry and debate fostered by glasnost, the study of the past has become both an eagerly shared passion and a bitter, divisive issue for Soviets, with the top man in the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> out in front with the calls for increased candor. `` One can not agree with those who propose that we forget our history or use only a certain part of it,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said in January. `` All this enables us to draw lessons for the present ... and to disclose more fully the potential of socialism and its values.'' But more than 3 -LCB- years into <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s rule it still is n't clear whether glasnost will bring unhampered historical scholarship and the right to differ on fundamental questions or just substitute one Kremlin orthodoxy for another. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> himself recently chaired the meeting of a special <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> commission preparing a new `` concise history'' of the party, showing how keenly he wants his influence to be felt in the new Soviet view of the past. School history texts, full of ritual self-congratulations, radiant socialist futures and cartoon-like heroes and villains, were thrown out and are being rewritten. Windows on the past, shut tight for years by the censor, have been opened. Soviets now jostle at lending libraries for works about the long-concealed `` blank spots'' in their history. The book most in demand is <PERSON> Anatoly </PERSON> <PERSON> Rybakov </PERSON>'s `` Children of the Arbat,'' a novel about the bloody swath cut through society by <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s political terror that left its traces of horror at <LOCATION> Kuropaty </LOCATION>. And history in the <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> era has meant the humbling of the memories of men who, while alive, were spoken of as the worthy spiritual heirs of Soviet founder <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
