<BYLINE>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</BYLINE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Dec. 4</NOTE>
<HEAD>MOSCOW: Vladimir I. Lenin.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> monument to <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON> was spirited away at night. A vandal at <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> spilled ink on a memorial plaque to former <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> ideologue <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Suslov </PERSON>. The city of <LOCATION> Izhevsk </LOCATION>, which once bore the name of <PERSON> Dmitri </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ustinov </PERSON>, spent more than $ 3.2 million to wipe the late defense minister's name off street signs, official stationery and railway timetables. For <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and his allies, history matters because it bares the mistakes of past <ORGANIZATION> Kremlin </ORGANIZATION> leaders and points away from what <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> wants to avoid: the totalitarianism and bureaucratic choke-hold on society that marred <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s rule, the erratic capriciousness of <PERSON> Nikita </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON>, the complacency and moral rot under <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON>. `` It is said that people learn from mistakes, and nations learn from tragedies. Let us learn,'' one author, <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ovrutsky </PERSON>, said in a newspaper article on Soviet history this year. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> also seeks to right what he regards as historical injustices. By rehabilitating some of the revolutionaries and visionaries <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> destroyed, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has been able to resurrect their once-discredited ideas as ideological underpinning for his own reforms. Training glasnost's spotlight back into the past has had sensational results. Among the revelations this year: _ <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON> reportedly was clinically dead at one point in 1976 but recovered at least partially and remained Soviet president until his death in 1982. _ <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> was described by one Soviet newspaper as a paranoid whose brain was damaged by a stroke. _ <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bukharin </PERSON> and other <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> foes shot as `` enemies of the people'' in the 1930s are now said to have been framed. Such reports have startled a country long fed a diet of reassuring Kremlin communiques. `` In the past two years, I have learned more than I did in the previous 50 years of my life,'' one middle-aged <PERSON> Muscovite </PERSON> recently told a newspaper. Predictably, the questioning, doubts and criticism, where before there was often only praise, have produced a backlash among Soviets who feel that their entire history, even the building of socialism itself, has been besmirched. `` I would very much like to understand: who needs, and why, to have every prominent leader of the party <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and the Soviet government compromised after he leaves office and discredited in connection with his actual or supposed mistakes and calculations ... Where did we get this passion for squandering the prestige and dignity of the leaders of the world's first socialist country?'' a <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> teacher wrote in the <ORGANIZATION> Sovietskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rossiya </ORGANIZATION> daily earlier in the year. The official response to that letter, signed by <PERSON> Nina </PERSON> <PERSON> Andreyeva </PERSON>, demonstrated how explosive the issue of history in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> can be _ and the limits still drawn on historical scholarship. Pravda, the party's principal organ, attacked its fellow newspaper for printing a document lauding <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> and forced <ORGANIZATION> Sovietskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rossiya </ORGANIZATION> to recant by printing the Pravda attack. Despite glasnost, <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> or <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON> are rarely defended in print. Since <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s policy is avowedly the opposite of theirs, praise for his predecessors could be, or might seem to be, an attack on <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> or his policy of change. But on the whole, glasnost has meant a dramatic widening of the historical field, and a coming to terms with some of the uncomfortable truths of the Soviet past that long lay hidden or were played down. Historian <PERSON> Fyodor </PERSON> <PERSON> Burlatsky </PERSON> was referring to the 1953-64 <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON> era, but might well have been speaking of all Soviet history, when he said: `` For a long time, a very long time, talking about those stormy years was not accepted practice. It was as if someone's hand had ripped out an entire chapter from our chronicle.''
</TEXT>
