</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MAGADAN, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Asir </PERSON> <PERSON> Sandler </PERSON> remembers the interrogation, the death sentence never carried out and the tiny knots he tied in pieces of string to remind him of what he saw in a Stalinist labor camp north of this capital of the Gulag. <PERSON> Trudy </PERSON> <PERSON> Richter </PERSON>, a German Communist whose nationality could n't save her, remembers the filthy, crowded ferry ride from <LOCATION> Vladivostok </LOCATION> to <PERSON> Magadan </PERSON>, and her husband who never returned. This city of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Far </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, like so much of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, is torn between the urge to remember and the desire to forget <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s purges that put it on the map and gave it the fearful reputation it still is trying to outlive. Thousands of <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s political prisoners were sent through <PERSON> Magadan </PERSON>, nothing more than a couple of stone buildings and wooden barracks in the 1930s, on their way north to the gold mines and labor camps of the <LOCATION> Kolyma </LOCATION> region of the far northeast. <PERSON> Sandler </PERSON>, 71, a native of <LOCATION> Baku </LOCATION> in the warm southern republic of <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>, spent the last several of his 10 years of labor camp as prisoner M-1-866 in a camp in the <LOCATION> Kolyma </LOCATION> region. He met with foreign reporters in <LOCATION> Magadan </LOCATION> recently to show them how he made the coded knots in pieces of string to record what he saw. Those strings, hidden in the camp and smuggled out by a means he still wo n't reveal, gave him some of the materials he has used to write about camp life. `` Your life there was hanging by a hair every minute,'' he said. `` You could be strangled by criminals for your portion of water and your piece of bread.'' Half-starved prisoners nevertheless were required to be neat, and even a loose corner on his number badge could mean 10 days in a punishment cell on only 200 grams of bread and a cup of boiled water a day. <PERSON> Sandler </PERSON> arrived in the <LOCATION> Magadan </LOCATION> region in 1947, already a prisoner for many years after being accused of spying for <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> during World War II. During a long interrogation, the charge eventually was reduced to carrying a poem in his pocket that insulted <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>. A military tribunal in <LOCATION> Baku </LOCATION> sentenced him to be shot, but allowed him to ask for clemency and then let him sit for another 90 days while the stress built up and his weight dropped from 70 kilograms -LRB- 154 pounds -RRB- to 42 kilograms -LRB- 92 pounds -RRB-. In the end, he realized `` it was better to be a spy than to threaten <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Sandler </PERSON> said. `` I understood that if I did n't sign what the investigator wanted, I would n't live another two months. Stories such as <PERSON> Sandler </PERSON>'s have given <PERSON> Magadan </PERSON> a reputation difficult to outlive. `` Magadan is regarded as a city of sad fate. This we remember and we know,'' Mayor <PERSON> Gennady </PERSON> <PERSON> Dorofeyev </PERSON> told the journalists. `` We ca n't reject this; we ca n't hide it. But when asked about building a monument to <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s victims, as <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and other cities are planning, officials point out the city already has a monument to <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> Berzin </PERSON>. <PERSON> Berzin </PERSON>, an official of the secret police organization that was responsible for opening up the <LOCATION> Far </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> with political prisoners, himself fell victim to <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
