</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By SID MOODY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILLINGTON N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It is hard to pinpoint just when a man decides to turn his back yard into a repair shop for wrecked birds. For <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Soucy </PERSON> it probably came 20 years ago when an anonymous someone, like an unwed mother abandoning her newborn in a basket at the church door, left a red-tailed hawk with a broken wing in a cardboard box on his front stoop. It was a challenge <PERSON> Soucy </PERSON> could n't say no to. He still ca n't. That is why his current back yard is an intensive care facility of assorted cages _ some the size of boxcars _ in which he endeavors to restore to the wild squadrons of sick and injured owls, hawks, eagles, falcons and selected songbirds. And the occasional lame duck. In earthly terms appropriate to a pirate's parrot, <PERSON> Soucy </PERSON> tells how birds have taken over his home, his bank account, his job and even his wife, <PERSON> Diane </PERSON>. `` Birds have eaten me up. They've consumed my life.'' These are the birds who came to dinner, as it were, for whose convalescence <PERSON> Soucy </PERSON> flies in 10,000 crickets a week from a <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> breeder, millions of grub worms from <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, grasshoppers galore from <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> and 150,000 rodents a year. `` I have 10,000 meal worms here right now, and they're just snacks,'' exclaims <PERSON> Soucy </PERSON> to whom sotto voce is an abomination. `` This cost $ 100,000 last year. If the food was n't donated, it would have cost $ 250,000. Just one rat costs $ 2.50. A mouse is $ 1.09. But I have to do it. No one else is going to.'' <PERSON> Soucy </PERSON> may have as many as 500 recovering birds at a time in his 100,000 cubic feet of cages. There's a barred owl on the mend from entanglement with a kite string. A golden eagle with a broken wing. Hawks shot by what <PERSON> Soucy </PERSON> calls unprintable `` slobs.'' Orphaned birds raised from infancy. An oriole that will winter over because it did not recover until after the last flight south. <PERSON> Soucy </PERSON> still tries to sandwich his profession as a self-employed tool and die pattern maker around a hobby that was once a Sopwith Camel and is now a B-52. This sometimes requires him to go to his paying job at 2 a.m. There are emergency calls at all hours. `` A bird gets hit, falls out of the nest. It does n't belong to the police. Not the dog warden. Does n't belong to anybody. So they say ` Call Soucy.''' A screech owl flies down a chimney and catches fire. Call Soucy. A goshawk crashes through a picture window and lands dazed on a coffee table. Call Soucy. `` There's nobody else to pass them to. The bird stops here.'' Last year, <PERSON> Soucy </PERSON>'s busiest yet, 1,485 wild birds ended up on his doorstep. This included 240 raptors, the carnivorous birds he specializes in. About half recovered and were returned to the wild. Repair is not cheap. `` To do an intramedulary fusion of a bird's wing bone with a pin can cost $ 400 for the operation. Post-op care can approach $ 1,000.'' Fortunately <PERSON> Soucy </PERSON> has two understanding veterinarians nearby _ Drs. <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Major </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Plainfield </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacobsen </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Basking </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ridge </LOCATION> _ who donate their surgical skills. `` We can keep a bird alive 90 percent of the time. But can we restore it 100 percent? The bird wo n't make it in the wild if it's only 75 percent So we keep about 100 for educational lectures at schools and such and euthenize the rest.'' <PERSON> Soucy </PERSON>'s preoccupation with raptors is evolutionary. He was born in <LOCATION> Cedar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grove </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, 57 years ago when it had some open land, not the 40,000 people it's packed with today. He learned nature from an uncle, a hunter, a species <PERSON> Soucy </PERSON> has no quarrel with despite the many gunshot-maimed birds he's treated. `` No competent, moral hunter will shoot hawks and owls. The bleeping slobs do.'' His interest was piqued years ago when he read an article in Audubon magazine on hawks. So he and <PERSON> Diane </PERSON> went out to <LOCATION> Hawk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> in eastern <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> to see the fall migration when thousands of raptors may fly by in a day riding the thermals south. `` I could n't imagine 1,000 hawks in the whole world much less overhead.'' Gunners used to shoot hundreds of birds in a day at <LOCATION> Hawk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> just to try their aim. This ended in 1934 when a wealthy woman from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, Mrs. <PERSON> Rosalie </PERSON> <PERSON> Edge </PERSON>, acquired the mountain as a refuge for the birds and birdwatchers. Cape May, an even bigger migrating junction at the tip of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, was another gunnery range. This stopped when the federal government outlawed shooting raptors in 1972. By then <PERSON> Soucy </PERSON> and <PERSON> Diane </PERSON> had been in the bird repair business for four years. They had rehabilitated that first red tail and released it. One thing led to another, so they bought a home in semi-rural land next to the Great Swamp Wildlife Refuge here. It started out as a backyard hobby, a gesture to right some of the wrongs committed by the biggest raptor of them all, man.
</TEXT>
