<FIRST>s a BC-APN--LampreyThreat ADV04-2Takes   11-21 0753</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Lamprey Threat, ADV 04-2 Takes,0768</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv04
^AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Dec. 4</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w
photo.)
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ Sea lampreys, eel-like creatures that attack
salmon and trout, are threatening the fishing industry at Lake
Champlain, the nation's sixth-largest freshwater lake. The lampreys,
which number in the tens of thousands, are finding new targets:
bass, pike, and in some cases, swimmers.</NOTE>
<TEXT>

</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KEKIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PLATTSBURGH, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Papineau </PERSON> still shudders at the memory of the slimy tangle of suction-cup-filled mouths and tooth-laden tongues in the fish tank at <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Richard </PERSON>'s Bait Shop. `` Absolutely gross. Horrible,'' she says. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> agrees: Sea lampreys are n't a pretty sight. Nonetheless, he's displayed them off and on for four years. With lampreys threatening the local sport-fishing industry, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> wants folks to know what they look like. `` It's real serious,'' says <PERSON> Richard </PERSON>, who also fishes commercially. `` I'd say if they do n't control them the lake will be dead within the next 10 years. They're getting on everything.'' No one knows for certain how the lampreys, which are indigenous to the ocean and have no natural predator, entered <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Champlain </LOCATION>. One theory suggests that they hitched rides on boats. Regardless of how they arrived, they've been there for over a century _ and lately, people who rely on the lake for their livelihoods do n't like what they're seeing. <PERSON> Goose </PERSON> <PERSON> Gagnon </PERSON> is one of them. He quit his job in a furniture factory last year to devote all his time to commercial fishing. `` There will be days when you come out and every fish you land has a -LRB- lamprey -RRB- hit on them, more than one,'' says <PERSON> Gagnon </PERSON>, who's been fishing the lake for over 30 years. `` Some I've cut open and I refuse to eat because the meat looked bad.'' <PERSON> Gagnon </PERSON>'s not alone. `` I've seen fish jump that had five or six -LRB- lampreys -RRB- on'em, and usually they're about 8 inches long,'' says <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON>, who moved to <LOCATION> Willsboro </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> three years ago. `` And they will stay with that fish as long as possible. In most cases that one hit does n't kill the fish. This is why you'll see fish with scars. And if they lose that fish they'll take another one, so they may go through three or four fish until they reach their full size.'' `` It's pretty severe,'' acknowledges <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Neff </PERSON>, an aquatic biologist with the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fisheries </ORGANIZATION>. `` Sea lamprey activity is intense, there's a big population, in the many tens of thousands. We should be seeing fish 8 to 15 pounds, and we just are n't seeing them. <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Champlain </LOCATION> historically had a tremendous population of <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> salmon, and that population went right down the tubes. It also had a good lake trout population, and that went right down the tubes.'' Lampreys are blamed for much of that loss. They spawn in wetlands and streams that feed the lake, and their larvae can live there for three or more years. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Jolliff </PERSON>, sea lamprey unit leader for the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fisheries </ORGANIZATION>, says one female might spawn up to 100,000 eggs at a time. And each lamprey can live up to 17 years, killing 40 pounds of fish during its life. Lampreys, which can grow longer than 20 inches, normally do their damage in the deepest extremities of their habitat. Using their mouths and tongues, the lampreys latch onto fish, bore holes in their sides and literally suck the life out of the fish until they are near death. These days the lampreys in <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Champlain </LOCATION> _ the sixth-largest freshwater lake in the nation _ are acting more like predators than the parasites they actually are. Their favorite targets are no longer just salmon and lake trout. `` They're hitting pike and bass _ scaly, warm-water fish that they never hit before,'' says <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, an outdoors writer who lives on the lake. `` I caught a lot of pike last year that were 32 inches long and only weighed three pounds. They were like stick fish.'' `` The lamprey bothers the lake trout and the salmon, but it's nothing compared to the job it's doing on the brown trout and the steelheads,'' says <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON>, who dealt with a similar problem in the Great Lakes when he worked for the <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> game department `` You do n't see a brown trout in here more than 2 years old.'' Fishermen, are n't the only ones feeling the effects.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881121-0225 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-88 1421EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-APN--LampreyThreat Adv04-1stAdd   11-21 0758</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Lamprey Threat, Adv 04-1st Add,0770</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv04</NOTE>
<BYLINE>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</BYLINE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Dec. 4</NOTE>
<HEAD>PLATTSBURGH, N.Y.: the effects.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 `` Swimmers are even being hit,'' says <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Assemblyman <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortloff </PERSON>, whose district borders the lake. `` What that tells us is that there are so many lamprey that they're indiscriminately attaching themselves to whatever swims by because there simply are n't enough trout and salmon in the lake to support them all.'' The situation has been getting worse since the mid-1970s _ ever since <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> began stocking hundreds of thousands of salmon and trout every year to make the 125-mile-long lake a sport-fishing Mecca. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> fisheries manager, says one reason for the stocking was to study the lamprey problem. `` Some people think we've dragged our feet,'' <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> says. `` But if we went ahead -LRB- and treated the lake without evaluating the situation -RRB- we'd have been hauled into the courts and we'd be there forever.'' Still, the study has taken nearly a decade and makes no sense to <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON>. `` Why on earth they ever did what they did is beyond me,'' he says. `` They re-created the fishery backward. They should have treated the lampreys first and then stocked the fish. They gave them food so, bang, the population soared.'' Last August, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Canadian </LOCATION> province of <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION> signed an agreement to work together to improve the lake. In addition, <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> are cooperating on a plan to control the lampreys. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Fish and <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Vermont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> have assembled a 433-page draft environmental impact statement in connection with a proposed lamprey control program. If it works, officials estimate 500 jobs would be created and increased sport fishing would generate $ 2.5 million to $ 3.5 million a year. The plan calls for two so-called `` lampricides'' to be applied twice, in four-year intervals, in 14 streams _ nine in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and five in <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> _ and five stream-delta areas. The experiment, which would begin next fall, would cost about $ 3 million. <ORGANIZATION> TFM </ORGANIZATION> is the main chemical that would be used. The amount applied kills lampreys but can be metabolized by most other fish and has not harmed water fowl, mammals or humans. It's been used extensively and successfully in the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION> and in two of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Finger Lakes -LRB- <LOCATION> Cayuga </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Seneca </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> -RRB- and has proven relatively harmless. The main detriment is that some non-target organisms _ invertebrates such as worms and insects on which fish feed _ will be killed, but not to any great extent, according to the environmental statement. <ORGANIZATION> Bayer </ORGANIZATION> 73, the other chemical, is used in other countries to treat tapeworm in humans and in this country to treat domestic animals. As usual, the notion of applying chemicals to the environment is creating apprehension. `` My organization is very concerned about the program and its impact,'' says <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulhern </PERSON>, associate director of the <ORGANIZATION> Vermont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, a privately funded citizen action group. `` We've been studying the environmental impact statement and identifying what we think are inadequacies with that report. We've found a lot of discrepancies between the environmental impact statement and information from the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> about the chemicals that are going to be used There's a lot more information that needs to be given to the public.'' Like VPIRG, the <ORGANIZATION> Lake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Champlain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, a natural resource advocacy group based in <LOCATION> Burlington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vt. </LOCATION>, has n't taken a stand on the matter yet, but its members are also concerned. `` We want to know alternatives,'' says spokeswoman <PERSON> Lori </PERSON> <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON>. `` We do n't want the public money to get only channeled into a proposal that would stimulate recreational trophy fishing. `` We ca n't lose sight of the fact that we have fish for human consumption significantly impacted by PCBs and chlordane. There's a rule to eat only one fish a month out of the lake. We need a considerable amount of money to find a solution to that. We ca n't lose sight of those types of problems We want people to look at the larger picture.'' New Yorkers got the chance to voice their views on the matter recently at hearings in <LOCATION> Ticonderoga </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Plattsburgh </LOCATION>, and sentiment favored treating the lake. Vermonters will get their turn at public hearings next February. Officials from both states will assess the public's reaction and decide whether to go ahead with the plan. For it to work, both states must cooperate.
</TEXT>
