<HEAD>Video View: Home Video News and Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Videos reviewed this week: `` Shakedown,'' `` The Moderns,'' `` Sleepaway Camp II.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` Shakedown'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> MCA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Entertainment </ORGANIZATION>; VHS-Beta, $ 89.95; Rated R -RRB-. Trashing <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s sleazy 42nd Street strip in a stupid chase scene is the emotional center of `` Shakedown,'' a violent, improbable crime thriller that lasted five minutes in theaters and went immediately to videocassette. It stars <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Weller </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Elliott </PERSON>, two talented and disciplined actors who must be thoroughly embarrassed by their involvement in this witless film, but struggle vainly to breathe some humanity into two-dimensional roles. The name of the screenwriter-director is being withheld to protect his career. Well, all right. It's <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Glickenhaus </PERSON>. That's G_L_I_C_K_E_N_H_A_U_S This ugly little movie plays like a sadistic Looney Tune, with 3.5 crazy chase scenes, a half-dozen explosions, psychotic, cartoonish behavior by practically everyone, pointless vulgarity and mayhem. <PERSON> Elliott </PERSON> is the cop pal of <PERSON> Weller </PERSON>, a lawyer about to marry and work for his fiancee's Daddy on Wall Street. His last case as a public defender is a self-defense plea for a crack dealer who's killed a crooked cop in a drug deal Of course, the lawyer's Old Flame is prosecuting the case and they hop into bed without a thought for the personal or legal ethics of the situation. As the crooked cops close in on Our Heros, there is much bashing and chasing and shooting and blowing up of things. If that's what you're looking for, this movie has it. _ By <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` The Moderns'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Nelson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Entertainment </ORGANIZATION>; VHS-Beta, $ 89.98; Rated R -RRB- Why would a woman take a bath lathered in tiers of pearls? It's certainly not the best way to get the neck clean Probably because <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Fiorentino </PERSON> already had read this silly script and expected to be surprised by a nude <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> Carradine </PERSON> who moments before was downstairs trying to sell a painting to her art-collector husband, <PERSON> Bertram </PERSON> <PERSON> Stone </PERSON>. Is n't it every woman's fantasy to make love on the bathroom floor wearing pearls and patches of soap bubbles? <PERSON> Carradine </PERSON>'s character is called <PERSON> Nick </PERSON> <PERSON> Hart </PERSON>, giving us <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> vs. Stone. So do n't ask who will end up with lovely, bathing-beauty <PERSON> Rachel </PERSON>. The raging husband -LRB- John Lone -RRB-, is abusive to <PERSON> Rachel </PERSON>, kicks <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> in the face in a boxing ring after challenging him to a duel and burns <PERSON> Modiglianis </PERSON> in the fireplace. After first, of course, cutting one of the model's breasts from the canvas because a critic said its nipple looked like a wart. Why does <PERSON> Rachel </PERSON> stay with <PERSON> Stone </PERSON>? Money. <PERSON> Hart </PERSON>, a starving painter, lives in a garret and even forges masters to survive. He could n't possibly buy the pouting, languid <PERSON> Rachel </PERSON> enough pearls in which to bathe Besides, this is <LOCATION> Bohemian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> of the 1920s, and writer-director <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rudolph </PERSON> presents these characters on the cutting edge of a new artistic era as single-dimensional saps and lunatics. He and co-writer <PERSON> Jon </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradshaw </PERSON> may have meant well, but the archness and self-conscious pretension with which they translate avant-garde to the screen sets one's teeth on edge. It's difficult to decide if they're insulting their audience or displaying their own intellectual shallowness. Probably both. The constant lapsing into French with sporadic subtitles is difficult to deal with, especially on the small screen. The literary references are obscure enough that if you do n't know them, you wo n't know what you're not missing. But when you do catch one, it's generally embarrassingly gee-whiz. `` The Moderns'' is a no-win endeavor: There's no enlightenment, nor any loving treatment of artistic eccentrics. Minor characters, including several drawn from real life, float through as proof that this was <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> and that it was bizarre. <PERSON> Gertrude </PERSON> <PERSON> Stein </PERSON> and <PERSON> Alice </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Toklas </PERSON> are spotted at their salon; <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> Hemingway </PERSON> is stupidly drunk in every bar. <PERSON> Genevieve </PERSON> <PERSON> Bujold </PERSON> and <PERSON> Geraldine </PERSON> <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON> give credibility to peripheral but stock roles. <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> <PERSON> Shawn </PERSON> plays <PERSON> Oiseau </PERSON>, a gossip columnist who dresses up like a dumpy middle-aged woman so he can go unobserved to his own funeral, where a graveside priest eulogizes him as having `` converted gossip into poetry.'' <PERSON> Oiseau </PERSON> gets off most of the goofier lines, including telling <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> at the railroad station: `` I just ran into <PERSON> Maurice </PERSON> <PERSON> Ravel </PERSON> in the men's room, but he did n't recognize me.'' Who would, in those high heels and cloche hat? <PERSON> Oiseau </PERSON> sashays past <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>, playing the besotted <PERSON> Hemingway </PERSON>, who is mumbling lines that conclude with `` <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> is a portable banquet.'' `` You should work on that,'' quips <PERSON> Oiseau </PERSON> with the hindsight we all have that it utimately will read `` Moveable Feast.'' As he and <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> head back to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Oiseau </PERSON> says he's glad to be leaving <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> because `` the imitators are imitiating the imitators Hollywood will be like a breath of fresh air.'' Amen. The city depicted here is not only stagnant, but bush-league. _ By <PERSON> Theasa </PERSON> <PERSON> Tuohy </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` Sleepaway Camp II: Unhappy Campers'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Nelson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Entertainment </ORGANIZATION>; VHS-Beta, $ 79.98; Rated PG -RRB- Dear Mommy and Daddy: Here I am at Camp Rolling Rock. <PERSON> Angela </PERSON>, our new counselor, is real neat. She plays a great guitar and sings real good, and loves to take us on nature hikes. Last night, one of the kids, <PERSON> Phoebe </PERSON>, told us about a 14-year-old boy who everybody picked on. Well, he killed a bunch of people six years ago at Camp Arawak. <PERSON> Angela </PERSON> got real mad at <LOCATION> Phoebe </LOCATION> for telling that story and took her back to the cabin. But we never saw <PERSON> Phoebe </PERSON> again. <PERSON> Angela </PERSON> told us the next day that she had to send her home. There are these other two girls who like to smoke cigarettes and stay up late with boys. <PERSON> Angela </PERSON> got real mad at them, too, and had to send them home. <PERSON> Angela </PERSON> gets mad at a lot of people and they disappear. I do n't think I like Camp Rolling Rock too much. I am not a happy camper. But please do n't let <PERSON> Angela </PERSON> send me home ...
