<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Cindy Walker Writes `Songs With A Face'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Cindy </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>, `` the queen of country music songwriters,'' has spent about half a century writing recognizable songs that have been recorded by such performers as <PERSON> Elvis </PERSON> <PERSON> Presley </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bing </PERSON> <PERSON> Crosby </PERSON>. The veteran composer, who lives in <LOCATION> Mexia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, has written more than 450 songs that have been recorded. She was a finalist this year for induction into the Country Music Hall of Fame. The best tunes, she said in a telephone interview, `` are songs with a face.'' `` You recognize them. You know them. It's like a person. They have a face that's outstanding. Other songs do n't have a face; you just hear them, that's all. The really good ones are few and far between.'' Two of her best known songs are `` You Do n't Know Me'' and `` Dream Baby.'' `` You Do n't Know Me'' has been recorded by more than 75 singers, including Presley, <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Charles </PERSON>, <PERSON> Eddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Vale </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilley </PERSON>. <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> wrote the song in the mid-1950s after <ORGANIZATION> Arnold </ORGANIZATION> suggested the title, although he had no music or lyrics to go with it. `` I was in <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION> for a music convention and he said, ` I've got a title for you. He said you've got to promise me to write it. I was flippant about it -LRB- the title -RRB- because it did n't strike me at the time,'' she said. `` It's about someone you think you know but you do n't. I came on home and two months later, I was sitting in my chair in my studio and that song just started singing itself. I was just carried away with it. `` It took me three weeks to finish. Then I called <PERSON> Eddy </PERSON> and sang it over the phone to him. He had forgotten about it, but he recorded it three weeks later.'' Her song `` Dream Baby'' was written in the mid 1960s and was a hit by <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Orbison </PERSON> and later <PERSON> Glen </PERSON> <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON> among others. `` It's been recorded by lots of people,'' she said. `` I hate to name names because I leave someone out.'' Some of her other songs include `` In the Misty Moonlight,'' `` Take Me in Your Arms and Hold Me,'' `` China Doll'' and tunes with a Western flavor such as `` Blue Canadian Rockies,'' `` My <LOCATION> Rancho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grande </LOCATION>,'' `` Lone Star Trail'' and `` You're From <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>.'' For the king of Western swing music, <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Wills </PERSON>, she wrote `` Bubbles in My Beer,'' `` Cherokee Maiden'' and `` Dusty Skies.'' Her first big break, though, came in 1942 when she accompanied her father, a cotton buyer, on a trip to <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>. They drove past the <LOCATION> Crosby </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Building </LOCATION> and she decided to try to make an appointment with <PERSON> Bing </PERSON> <PERSON> Crosby </PERSON>. `` I went into the office and asked for Mr. <PERSON> Crosby </PERSON>,'' she recalled. `` The secretary said <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> or which one. I did n't know there was but one. So I asked for the first one said named. It was <PERSON> Larry </PERSON>. He listened and I sang him the song. He said <PERSON> Bing </PERSON> had been looking for a Western song. He said, ` meet me here tomorrow and we'll let him hear it.' I did.'' As a result, `` Lone Star Trail'' was recorded by <PERSON> Bing </PERSON> <PERSON> Crosby </PERSON> and became her first song recorded by someone else. `` It started me off,'' she said. Later, she signed her own recording contract with <ORGANIZATION> Decca </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Records </ORGANIZATION>. For five years she was a performer and songwriter and appeared in a few movies but eventually decided to concentrate on composing. `` I've always been a songwriter,'' she said. `` Everything was an offshoot from my writing.'' Her procedure has been to think of a title and then go from there. `` The title tells the story. If you can get a real good title, you've got something. I always write from the title. I've never written a song without the title.'' Melodies flow from the lyrics, she said. `` The words and music come together. It just sort of comes to you. The songs just sing themselves to me. They kind of write themselves. I just stand back and listen.'' <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>, who gives her age as `` old enough to know better and young enough not to care,'' is still writing. Her song, `` Sugar Moon,'' has recently been recorded by country stars <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Janie </PERSON> <PERSON> Frickie </PERSON> and K.D. <PERSON> Lang </PERSON>. `` I write all the time. It's all I've ever done,'' she said.
