<HEAD>Learning the Basics and Having Fun, Too</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Why use a book to teach children about the life cycle of the butterfly when they can witness metamorphosis? `` One is an aesthetic, hair-raising experience that is just absolutely dramatic beyond belief. The other, all it is is just reading another set of symbols,'' said <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pottenger </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, director of science projects for the Curriculum, <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hawaii </ORGANIZATION>. Substituting words for nature's wonders, unfortunately, is `` what most of science has been'' over the years, said <PERSON> Pottenger </PERSON>. `` You destroy science that way. You literally destroy science by putting it into that form.'' <PERSON> Pottenger </PERSON>, 60, a former high school science teacher, has developed a teaching program that replaces books with `` real world'' lessons. Developmental Approaches in Science and Health integrates science, health and technology with subjects such as literature and social studies. DASH is the elementary equivalent to his Foundational Approaches in Science Teaching a middle school program used by more than 1,200 districts nationwide. He had started FAST in 1966, with money from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hawaii </ORGANIZATION> and the state, to take advantage of <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>'s `` natural museum'' environment. It was introduced in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> in 1970 and spread to the mainland in 1976, being tailored to reflect each district's needs and natural surroundings `` We wanted to look at the real world in which the child lived, rather than the textbook world,'' <PERSON> Pottenger </PERSON> said. In DASH, instead of lecturing on the importance of sanitation, for example, teachers are encouraged to whip up some `` germy goo'' out of cocoa and cooking oil that children can dip their fingers into while listening to a poem or two: `` There once was a terrible germ, who was long and looked like a worm. His favorite trick was to get people sick, so they'd lie on their back and squirm.'' Such strategies work wonders, said <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Baldwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Children </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Carnegie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mellon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, a campus laboratory school for research in child development. `` If language arts and math and science and you-name-it are all together ... all of a sudden, the kids click, click, click,'' she said, snapping her fingers. `` ` Oh, I get it. I understand and I can use it here, here, here and here.''' Kindergarten teacher <PERSON> Gloria </PERSON> <PERSON> Cannon </PERSON>, whose laboratory school is affiliated with the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Buffalo </LOCATION>, is just as enthusiastic about what she calls DASH's `` whole world'' and `` capturing-the-moment'' approach. `` It allows for the individual. It's not this is the right answer or the wrong answer. There are many right answers for the same thing, and many ways to solve one particular problem,'' <PERSON> Cannon </PERSON> said. The trick is getting students to see how science touches their lives. `` Once the child understands and can use the material to understand their world around them, they're hooked for life,'' Ms. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said. `` It's when the child does n't understand ... that you lose them. They just turn it off.'' DASH was incorporated this fall into kindergarten and first-grade curriculums at 10 laboratory schools, which are the same as any other school except for affiliation with universities. Course materials are expected to be ready for grades two through six in 1991. It eventually will be offered, like FAST, to public schools willing to buy the material and have their teachers trained by a special team of instructors. `` The major problem has been that elementary teachers generally have been frightened by science because they are fearful they're going to make a mistake,'' <PERSON> Pottenger </PERSON> said `` It's much easier to return to the textbook, which gives all the proper answers.'' With DASH, he said, teachers look not `` so much at textbook answers but real phenomenon. The phenomenon tell you whether or not you have actually a proper interpretation.''
</TEXT>
