<NOTE>For release Thursday, Nov. 24, and thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>New Advances Will Broaden Use of Custom-Made Joint Implants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DUESSELDORF, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Advances in computer imaging techniques and biomedical research will significantly expand the use of custom-made joint and bone implants in the coming years, specialists say. `` The technology and research is moving at a far greater pace than we expected,'' said orthopedic surgeon Dr. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Stulberg </PERSON>, one of several hundred doctors, reseachers and other specialists at the first international symposium on custom-made prostheses here last month. `` We have learned that a great deal is being done in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> that we can profit from,'' said <PERSON> Stulberg </PERSON>, of <ORGANIZATION> Northwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. He said he was impressed by a method developed by <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> researchers to reduce the distortion in test images of implanted metal joints, allowing doctors to better judge the success of the operation. Custom-made joint replacements are a relatively new development in orthopedic surgery, and their use is not yet widespread, <PERSON> Stulberg </PERSON> said. `` The use of custom-made joint replacements is growing by about 100 percent a year. Their use will spread as orthopedic surgeons learn more about them.'' Follow-up studies of patients who have received custom-made joints indicate they perform better than traditional `` off the shelf prostheses,'' he said. Most replacement hip, knee, ankle, elbow, shoulder and finger joints are made in a small range of sizes designed to fit average-sized patients. However, such devices do n't fit all patients and certain medical conditions require the use of a custom-made prostheses. With the use of sophisticated computer and design technology, the devices can be constructed to give a `` near perfect fit,'' said <PERSON> Clyde </PERSON> <PERSON> Pratt </PERSON>, president of <LOCATION> Techmedica </LOCATION>, a <LOCATION> Camarillo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, company that makes replacement joints. `` We think this is the method of the future,'' <PERSON> Pratt </PERSON> said, adding that the costs of custom-made devices should go down as research costs decline. Custom-fitted joints now can cost up to twice as much as non-custom replacements.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Nov. 24</NOTE>
