 An <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> beverage producer hoping for spirited competition with the Soviets has begun bottling vodka made with glacier water. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Alaska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mountaintop </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Spirits </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said the <LOCATION> Attakiska </LOCATION> vodka that his firm began bottling in November will be sold intially in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> and in Eastern states, with sales later expected to reach other parts of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> plus some <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rim </LOCATION> nations. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said he expects an immediate monthly demand for 2,000 to 3,000 cases of the new vodka. Three percent of total sales are targeted for <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, he said. `` While people are, on the whole, drinking less, they are more discriminating in what they are drinking,'' <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said. `` Today's consumer is more sophisticated and is willing to spend the few extra dollars it takes to buy the best vodka available. He also said he is relying on the <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> mystique to draw people to the product for a first-time sip. `` The mystique and character of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> will be key to breaching the stronghold of the established market leaders,'' <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said. The production process is described as one that takes the Soviet method a step further through use of `` the pure and distinctive glacier waters available in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'' and through a special finishing process. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said he has been working with a <LOCATION> Stamford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, marketing firm to launch the vodka. His other products include <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> bottled water and bagged beverage ice chipped from <LOCATION