 <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> LeClerc </PERSON> clearly is one guy you would n't want to mess with on the wrestling mat _ or in the kitchen. At 24, <ORGANIZATION> LeClerc </ORGANIZATION> has a solid hold on two divergent careers. In fact, when they're in season, many of the wrestlers who train under <ORGANIZATION> LeClerc </ORGANIZATION> try to think about anything but food. Making weight is all that matters and the delicacies that come out of <ORGANIZATION> LeClerc </ORGANIZATION>'s kitchen would n't help that cause. `` They have joked about it,'' <PERSON> LeClerc </PERSON> says of the wrestlers he coached at <ORGANIZATION> Troy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> last season. `` They would make comments like, ` Are you going to make us something to eat after practice, coach?''' As a macho sport, wrestling seems to have little in common with catering. But <PERSON> LeClerc </PERSON> points to the precision of preparing a special food dish and the technique needed to successfully perform a difficult wrestling move. <PERSON> LeClerc </PERSON>'s business, called Charmont, is busier than ever these days. With wrestling season coming, the gas on the stove will be turned down as the heat on the mat is turned up. <PERSON> LeClerc </PERSON> is in his first season as head coach at <ORGANIZATION> Southfield </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, where the wrestling program has been lackluster in recent years. When athletic director <PERSON> Art </PERSON> <PERSON> Carinci </PERSON> heard <PERSON> LeClerc </PERSON> was a caterer, he was pleased. `` My reaction was, ` That sounds great. He could cater our sports banquet,''' <PERSON> Carinci </PERSON> says. But <PERSON> Carinci </PERSON> says <PERSON> LeClerc </PERSON> was hired for his wrestling, not his culinary, credentials. After the job was posted among teachers and staff, <PERSON> Carinci </PERSON> interviewed and h