<HEAD>FOOD: Rockefeller Center</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE SCHROEDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With more than 25,000 restaurants within its borders, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> might well be considered the culinary crossroads of the world. Diners can choose from what the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Visitors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> describes as a `` cornucopia of international cuisines,'' including Brazilian, Cajun, Chinese, French, German, Greek, Indian, Italian, Japanese, Mexican, Russian, Spanish, Thai or Vietnamese specialties. But at Rockefeller Center, in the very heart of <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>, patrons also might encounter such attractions as `` Breakfast at the O.K. Corral,'' lunch selections from `` The Firefighter's Cookbook,'' or a dinner menu built around recipes borrowed from the tasty meals served to <ORGANIZATION> Ringling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Barnum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON> circus performers. Such offbeat items are most often seen on the menus of the American Festival Cafe, one of three restaurants wrapped around the famed ice-skating rink -LRB- which becomes an open air garden cafe during the warm weather season -RRB-. The other two eateries are the elegant Sea Grill, which specializes in seafood, and Savories, a casual restaurant geared to speedy service and takeout delectables. The emphasis at all three is on all-American dining. The wine list is strictly domestic and the beer choices feature regional American brews. Customers at the American Festival when the `` O.K. Corral'' breakfast was offered in 1986 found such imaginative menu offerings as apples baked in bourbon, eggs scrambled with frizzled beef jerky, oatmeal flapjacks with molasses-stewed prunes and Judge <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Bean </PERSON>'s beans <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON> <PERSON> Epstein </PERSON>, who has helped plan and promote such off-the-beaten-track themes since the restaurant opened four years ago, explains how beans usually were prepared in the judge's `` Wild West'' days: `` By the time the pale pink beans called <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> strawberries had cooked all night in their covering of bourbon, onions, molasses, salt pork and spices, the bourbon's alcohol had entirely evaporated, leaving behind only the mellow smoky flavor of <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>'s pride as a reminder of the previous evening's carouse.'' According to <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Epstein </PERSON>, public relations consultant for <ORGANIZATION> Restaurant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION>, which operates the three eateries, adopting new themes and changing menus several times a year is not a simple task _ especially when the restaurant serves about 450,000 meals annually, matching the combined total of 450,000 meals served at the other two restaurants. `` It's not the easiest thing in the world to do with a restaurant, because change _ as it is for people _ is difficult for restaurants. You have to extend yourself to change rather than keep on doing the same thing,'' she explains. `` Changing a menu requires an extraordinary pulling together of a very large team. Everybody has to cooperate when you have a change ... When I have an idea _ sometimes even supplying recipes for them _ the chef is always there because the cooking people are involved from the beginning. `` There's also the purchasing and marketing departments, and the liquor buyers, and so on. Then when the new menu is set and tested and ready to be printed on paper it involves everybody in the restaurant who serves it. `` There are meetings by our management staff to teach people who serve it what it is, how it looks, how it tastes, how it's served.'' When `` firehouse cooking'' was the theme early last year, the program was billed as a tribute to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s firehouse chefs. All of the recipes were created by firefighters and most were taken from <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sineno </PERSON>'s best-selling `` The Firefighter's Cookbook.'' During the testing of the chef's cooking of recipes being considered for the menu, the Firefighters Tasting Panel discovered something new, Miss <PERSON> Epstein </PERSON> recalls. As she explained in the American Festival newsletter: `` They pointed out that there must be some mistake in the manicotti _ delicious as it was -LRB- and please pass some more -RRB- theirs had never had a sauce like that. It took our forensic team some time to determine that two recipes had inadvertently been combined and that <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> <PERSON> Prince </PERSON>'s manicotti had been topped with a sauce based on his artichoke pie. Thus are great dishes born.'' It was named `` Manicotti with Accidental Sauce'' and was the first dish to earn a place on the firehouse cooking menu. The circus theme featured a menu recalling the days when <ORGANIZATION> Ringling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> and company played under canvas and traveled on a train a hundred cars long, carrying some 1,400 people, lions, tigers and elephants. The fun menu, `` The Cooking of the Circus Stars,'' was printed in red, white and blue and borrowed the traditional hyperbole of circus promotions. It declared the offerings as `` The Most Gorgeous and Princely Spectacle of Monumental Magnificence Ever Beforked.''
