<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar inched up against the Japanese yen today in cautious trading following last week's concerted central bank interventions, while share prices continued to rise on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. The dollar closed at 122.52 yen, up 0.12 yen from Friday's close of 122.40 yen. Opening at 122.40 yen, the currency moved within a tight range of 122.37 yen to 122.60 yen. `` The dollar-yen rate did n't move very much today mainly because market players have become extremely cautious after the intervention by world's major central banks Thursday and Friday,'' said a dealer with <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, speaking on condition of anonymity. `` Investors were selling the dollar less, but very few people were interested in buying the currency,'' he said, adding that it was not dollar-buying interest that saved the dollar from falling further but cautiousness over the central bank intervention. Dealers said the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> did not intervene today. The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which gained 103.39 points to close at a record high of 29,180.20 Friday, added 104.06 points or 0.36 percent to finish at a new record of 29,284.26. The Nikkei rose 119.00 points shortly after the market opened, and managed to maintain the gain, rising for the seventh straight session since Nov. 11. `` Financial issues attracted participants largely because of the yen's strength against the dollar,'' said a dealer with <ORGANIZATION> Nomura </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s largest brokerage. `` But on the other hand, many market players were quite afraid that share prices were getting too high,'' the dealer said, asking he not be identified. In moderate trading, volume was est