<HEAD>Tobacco: Marketing Officials Optimistic As Burley Season Opens</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> WINSTON-SALEM </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ Despite a third straight year of drought, officials say the burley tobacco going to market today will be larger and higher in quality than last year's crop. The market opens this week in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> and seven other states, and marketing officials are cautiously predicting that farmers will have a better selling season this year than last year. `` I think the price average will be up, but that will mainly be because of the higher quality,'' said <PERSON> Joey </PERSON> <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON>, who operates the two tobacco warehouses in <PERSON> Boone </PERSON> with his father. Last year, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> burley prices averaged $ 150.87 per hundred pounds, down from the previous season's average of $ 156.01. This season's federal price support average will be $ 1.50 a pound, up by slightly more than 1 cent. By grades, the support will range from 98 cents to $ 1.63, the same as last season. `` It's looking a lot better than it did in July before the rains came,'' said Ed French of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal-State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Market </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>. A larger crop is expected this year because of more planted acreage and slightly higher yields, he said The Nov. 1 crop survey estimates the crop at 538.9 million pounds for the eight-state burley belt, up from last year's 486.6 million pounds. Yields are projected at 2,043 pounds an acre, up from 1,943 pounds last year. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>'s burley crop is expected to total 15.3 million pounds, up from 14.1 million last year. Yields are projected at 1,800 pounds an acre, slightly more than last year's 1,785 pounds. <LOCAT