<TEXT>
 Negotiations between the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sun-Times </ORGANIZATION> and its unionized editorial employees resumed this morning, hours before a threatened walkout by the writers, editors, photographers and support staff. A strike deadline of 2:30 p.m. CST today was set by the negotiating committee of <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspaper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Local </ORGANIZATION> 71, though the deadline could be changed, said <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lehman </PERSON>, the newspaper's religion writer and a union spokesman Talks resumed at 9 a.m., said <ORGANIZATION> Sun-Times </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Soll </PERSON>. But he added that `` at this time, it looks like 2:30 would be as far as we can go.'' <PERSON> Soll </PERSON> said newspaper negotiators were willing to meet around the clock, and that he hoped the talks would be fruitful. `` There appears to be much less anguish and much more hope'' among negotiators on both sides, he said. Salary remained the main sticking point. The Sun-Times' negotiators `` have not yet made their final offer,'' <PERSON> Soll </PERSON> said, adding he expected that offer to be made at today's meeting. Union leaders met late Sunday night and agreed to accept the company proposal for a bargaining session today. `` We'll keep negotiating until we have a settlement or until we hit the strike deadline, and then we're out of there,'' said <PERSON> Shane </PERSON> <PERSON> Gericke </PERSON>, a copy editor and member of the negotiating committee for the union, which represents 250 reporters, editors, photographers and support staff. `` We decided to give it every shot,'' he said. A strike by <ORGANIZATION> Sun-Times </ORGANIZATION> editorial workers would be the first in the newspaper's 40-year history. <PERSON> Soll </PERSON> said management did not want a strike, but is `` fully prepared to produce a paper'' using company executives, non-union editors and outside writers. He said the newspaper would continue putting out its three daily editions. Union members have been working without a contract since June 1. As the strike deadline approached, guild unit chairman <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibbons </PERSON> said the union would walk out if the company continued to refuse to offer a pay raise. The guild has been seeking a 19.5 percent pay raise over three years, while management's latest proposal was for a 3 percent salary cut for 18 months, followed by a restoration of current pay levels for the remainder of the three-year pact, <PERSON> Gibbons </PERSON> said. `` We've got to have pay raises in the contract for this to be settled,'' he said. In addition, <PERSON> Gibbons </PERSON> said, differences remained over management proposals to cut night differential for workers by 40 percent and exempt eight senior editorial staffers from union jurisdiction. <PERSON> Soll </PERSON> said `` the paper is healthy financially'' but must control its costs to remain competitive with the larger <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION>, which has an estimated circulation of 765,000 daily and 1.117 million Sunday. The <ORGANIZATION> Sun-Times </ORGANIZATION>, whose circulation is estimated at 605,000 daily and 614,000 on Sunday, was purchased from <LOCATION> Australian </LOCATION> media baron <PERSON> Rupert </PERSON> <PERSON> Murdoch </PERSON> for $ 145 million in June 1986 by a group of investors led by the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Adler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Shaykin </PERSON>.
