<TEXT>
 Futures prices of grain and soybeans were mixed early in today's session on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> in light, pre-Thanksgiving trading. `` We might already be entering a holiday-type market: thin trade, quiet markets, light volume,'' said <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Lespinasse </PERSON>, a trader with <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. Most soybean futures were fractionally higher on technical factors but reports of weekend rain in the soybean regions of <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> were keeping a rein on the rally, analysts said. Grain prices were mostly lower with little fresh news to pull prices one way or the other. In early trading, wheat was unchanged to 1 cent lower with the contract for delivery in December at $ 4.10 \ a bushel; corn was 1 \ cents lower to -RCB- cent higher with December at $ 2.58 a bushel; oats were -RCB- cent lower to -LCB- cent higher with December at $ 2 a bushel; soybeans were \ cent lower to 1 -LCB- cents higher with January at $ 7.31 -LCB- a Livestock and meat futures were mostly lower in early trading on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Live cattle were .25 cent lower to .27 cent higher with December at 72.62 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .35 cent lower with January at 81.65 cents a pound; live hogs were .35 cent lower to .10 cent higher with December at 40.25 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .02 cent to .35 cent lower with February at 42.90 cents a pound. Livestock and meat futures closed lower on Friday.
