<HEAD>EEC Commissioner Calls for Joint Merger Policy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>'s competition commissioner said Monday it was essential that the 12 <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> states forge a joint merger control policy. `` National laws are simply not adequate to deal with cross-border mergers, in particular those which may have an effect upon the Community as a whole,'' Commissioner <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Sutherland </PERSON> said in a speech. Last week, <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> states agreed to empower the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> to consider corporate mergers in advance, and maybe block them. But the <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> is seeking the power to rule on mergers exceeding a billion European currency units, which are worth about $ 1.19 billion, in annual revenue. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> want that limit raised. Urging speedy adoption of a merger control policy, <PERSON> Sutherland </PERSON> said differing national rules on mergers which may lead to conflicting decisions. `` This is a severe handicap for the companies concerned who are entitled to expect greater legal certainty and more rapid procedures,'' he said. He said companies increasingly view the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> countries as `` their home market. It is now widely acknowledged that if the economic objectives underpinning the single market strategy are to be achieved, a streamlined Community merger control mechanism must be available.'' <PERSON> Sutherland </PERSON> spoke at a conference organized by the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> daily <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>'s plans to knock down trade barriers among its member nations by Dec. 31, 1992. He said while the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> members adopted a modest airline deregulation plan in 1987, `` we have to go further.'' He said the Commission has begun drafting proposals for a second stage of liberalization. These will deal with ending curbs on capacity and prices and freeing air carriers of the system of slot allocation at airports that now favors major airlines at the expense of smaller competitors, <PERSON> Sutherland </PERSON> said. He said the Commission also planned to tackle air transportation agreements between <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> nations and other countries. `` There is now a good case for the negotiation of air service agreements between the Community and other nations ... The present network of bilateral agreements has resulted in an unduly rigid international air transport system,'' he said.
