<DATELINE>MIDDLETOWN, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Armco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and a major Japanese steelmaker Monday announced their intention to form a joint venture to operate <ORGANIZATION> Armco </ORGANIZATION>'s Eastern Steel Division. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Boni </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Armco </ORGANIZATION>'s chairman and chief executive officer, said <ORGANIZATION> Armco </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Kawasaki </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> reached agreement in principle to form the venture to jointly manage and operate the Middletown-based <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Division </ORGANIZATION>, which includes <ORGANIZATION> Armco </ORGANIZATION>'s steel mills in <LOCATION> Middletown </LOCATION> and in <LOCATION> Ashland </LOCATION>, Ky. The division employs 13,800 people, has annual sales of about $ 1.5 billion and annual production capacity of approximately 3.5 million tons of steel. The proposed terms of the joint venture provide for <ORGANIZATION> Kawasaki </ORGANIZATION> to purchase 40 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Armco </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> Division for about $ 350 million with <ORGANIZATION> Armco </ORGANIZATION> retaining the rest. Language in the agreement allows for the two companies to negotiate an increase in <LOCATION> Kawasaki </LOCATION>'s investment in the venture up to a maximum of 50 percent, officials said. The proposed venture would assume the debts and employee benefit obligations related to the division's operation. <PERSON> Boni </PERSON> said the joint venture would provide new steelmaking technology for <ORGANIZATION> Armco </ORGANIZATION>'s carbon steel business, would give the Japanese steelmaker a stake in a major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> steel company and would allow the two firms to better serve Japanese automakers in the <LOC