<HEAD>OPEC Ministers Warned About Falling Oil Prices</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 new graf after 5th graf pvs He said ... to ADD
settlement price on New York Merc. Picks up 6th graf pvs Lukman said
...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> ministers quickly adjourned their formal talks Monday and resumed private negotiations aimed at resolving a dispute between <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> that is holding up a new production agreement. The ministers met for about 90 minutes before putting off their formal talks until Wednesday. President <PERSON> Rilwanu </PERSON> <PERSON> Lukman </PERSON> opened the winter meeting of the 13-nation Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries by appealing for compromise. He said cartel members must reach a new accord limiting their oil production or risk a `` serious erosion'' of crude prices. `` It may be necessary to take one step back now from our deep-seated principles and beliefs in order to take two steps forward at a later date,'' he said. He said the cartel's problems `` are formidable and yet they are not insuperable.'' Crude oil prices edged higher on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> in light trading as the market awaited definitive news on the progress of the talks. Contracts for January delivery of <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION>, the benchmark <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude, rose 7 cents from Friday's close to settle at $ 12.98 cents per 42-gallon barrel <PERSON> Lukman </PERSON> said they had not yet discussed the crucial questions of oil production, output quotas for member countries and pricing. A few hours after the meeting, the ministers resumed some of the private discussions they have been holding since late last week to try to resolve the issues separating <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. The main obstacle has been <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s insistence on a production ceiling equal to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. Iranian Oil Minister <PERSON> Gholamreza </PERSON> <PERSON> Aghazadeh </PERSON> met with his Algerian counterpart, <PERSON> Sadek </PERSON> <PERSON> Boussena </PERSON>, who appears to have become an emissary between <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> countries. After the meeting, <PERSON> Aghazadeh </PERSON> told reporters it was still too early to tell whether an agreement would be reached or not. Consultations, he said, will continue Tuesday. `` If we should -LRB- see -RRB- some proposal that is good, we accept,'' he said. The ministers want to work out a new arrangement giving each country a production quota. They want to include <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> in the system. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> refused to join in the current accord arranged in 1986. `` I would be happier if I was inside the agreement,'' said Iraqi Oil Minister <PERSON> Issam </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> <PERSON> Raheem </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Chalabi </PERSON>. <PERSON> Aghazadeh </PERSON> again said he would oppose quota parity with <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. The two countries have had different ceilings for some time, he said. <LOCATION> Saudia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> have said they will not join a new quota system unless all 13 members belong. The ministers want to use the new accord to cap their runaway production and lift weak prices. <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> maintains a benchmark price of $ 18 a barrel but prices have been well under that. <PERSON> Lukman </PERSON> told the ministers, `` As we are all aware, prices have been hovering $ 5 to $ 6 per barrel below our targeted levels for several months now.'' `` If we do not reach such an accord,'' he said, `` then I am afraid we may see a further serious erosion of these price levels, to our mutual detriment.'' <PERSON> Aghazadeh </PERSON> said he has offered to meet with <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION> to work out the quota dispute. `` We can sit down to solve -LRB- the -RRB- problem -LRB- and have a -RRB- discussion about any matter,'' he said. `` I am very flexible.'' He also said <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> wants <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> to give it a higher ceiling in any new agreement. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> needs more revenues from its oil to help rebuild after the 8-year war with <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. He said <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> will be able within a year to boost its production of oil to more than 4 million barrels a day. The country, he said, is currently pumping more than 3 million barrels a day and will boost that to about 3.3 million in a few months. Under the current production agreement, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> has a ceiling of 2.4 million barrels a day. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, although it refused to join the current accord, has an allotment of 1.5 million barrels a day. Analysts estimate that <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> has been producing at least 2.6 million barrels a day, an amount that could soar to 3.7 million barrels in mid-1989 with completion of a new pipeline through <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> to the Red Sea. <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s current output accord sets total production at about 15 million barrels a day for 12 countries. Total cartel production in October was estimated by the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> at nearly 21.1 million barrels, the highest monthly level in more than five years. <PERSON> Aghazadeh </PERSON> has proposed that <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> be given `` export parity'' with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. That would allow <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> to have a higher overall ceiling to account for its larger internal oil demand, which it estimates at 1 million barrels a day. A possibility for resolving the dispute, analysts suggested, would be to give <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> a lower quota on paper. But the difference in the ceilings would be made up by letting <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> keep a portion of the oil produced in an area called the neutral zone, which is shared by <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>. The discussions began Thursday evening when the two <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> committees _ price evolution and long-term strategy _ held formal talks. Countries belonging to those panels are <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>. Other members are <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Gabon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Qatar </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION>.
