<HEAD>Report Says Regions Dependent On Manufacturing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Manufacturing jobs are growing faster in traditional service-sector areas and declining throughout the once-booming rust-belt states, according to a new report Monday by the <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> are among the beneficiaries of a new geographical realignment of manufacturing, the report by the business-financed research organization said. Meanwhile, manufacturing job growth is continuing to decline in states like <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, once the guts of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industrial heartland. `` Employment gains in the manufacturing sector this year will spread more widely than ever across the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' says <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Malin </PERSON>, a specialist in economic trends. `` Before the next national recession, <ORGANIZATION> Southeastern </ORGANIZATION> and Western states will have added substantially more manufacturing jobs than states in the North and East.'' Seven major states have added more than 738,000 manufacturing jobs since 1982, the report said. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> was in the lead with 228,900, followed by <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> with 114,500. In the last two years, however, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> has lost 66,000 manufacturing jobs, the board said. Also gaining manufacturing jobs since 1982 were <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> 91,400; <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> 90,600; <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> 78,600; <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> 78,300; and <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> 55,400. Among the losers were <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> with 7,300 jobs lost since 1982; <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> 29,500; <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> 34,700; <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> 43,300; <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> 52,000; <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> 63,700; and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> 88,900. The <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said the key to manufacturing success next year will be construction, defense spending and exports.
