<HEAD>LTV Posts $1.24 Billion Loss in Third Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> reported on Monday a third-quarter net loss of $ 1.24 billion, which company officials attributed largely to Chapter 11-related special charges. A change in accounting principles for post-employment medical and life insurance benefits also had a negative impact on results, officials of the diversified company said. The loss compares with a net profit of $ 109.7 million, or 91 cents a share, in the third quarter of 1987. <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> officials said the special charges and the accounting change are important elements in moving the company toward its Chapter 11 reorganization. `` Because <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> is in Chapter 11, we believe it is appropriate for the company to record all its liabilities, including the liability for these post-employment benefits, so that they may be appropriately dealt with in the reorganization process,'' said <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Hay </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION>'s chairman and chief executive officer. <PERSON> Angela </PERSON> <PERSON> Tese </PERSON>, a bankruptcy specialist for <ORGANIZATION> Cole </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Deitz </PERSON> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said Monday's announcement of a negative net worth was not a good signal for the company. `` They'll have to prove to the -LRB- bankruptcy -RRB- court that the plan is feasible,'' <PERSON> Tese </PERSON> said. `` They are going to have to be able to demonstrate to the court that they are healthy enough and that they wo n't have to reorganize again sometime soon.'' The third-quarter special charges total $ 1.34 billion, ost of which is non-cash. They include: _ $ 950 million for Chapter 11 creditors' claims; _ $ 350 million for a reduction of assets and other anticipated costs in the divesture of <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s bar business, as well as additional costs incurred in the rationalization of other steel facilities; _ $ 41 million for the write-off of goodwill recorded in connection with the company's 1983 acquisition of <ORGANIZATION> Sierra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. Without the two elements, <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> said its net income would have been $ 132.2 million for the third quarter and $ 453.7 million for the first nine months of the year. That would have compared with $ 109.7 million and $ 362.0 million for the respective periods in 1987. The change in accounting principle alters the method of accounting for post-employment medical and life insurance benefits and resulted in a one-time, non-cash charge of $ 2.26 billion, recorded as of last Jan. 1. `` The accounting method adopted by <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> recognizes the post-employment medical and life insurance benefits earned by all of the company's retirees and active employees,'' <PERSON> Hay </PERSON> said. `` Previously these costs were recognized only as they were paid.'' The change in accounting principle reduced operating income by $ 32.1 million for the third quarter and $ 98.2 million for the nine-month period. For the first nine months, <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> reported a net loss of $ 3.25 billion, which company officials also attributed to the special charges and accounting change. That compared with a net profit of $ 362.0 million, or $ 3.07 a share, in the same nine-month period of 1987.
