<HEAD>Jurors Claim Improprieties In Searle IUD Case Deliberations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge will hear motions next month stemming from three jurors' claims that they were intimidated into voting for an $ 8.15 million judgment against the maker of the Copper 7 intrauterine device, <ORGANIZATION> Monsanto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. <ORGANIZATION> Monsanto </ORGANIZATION>, whose <ORGANIZATION> G.D. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Searle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary manufactured the Copper 7, on Monday released a letter that the jurors sent to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Renner </PERSON>, who presided over the trial. The jury on Sept. 9 awarded the damages to <PERSON> Esther </PERSON> <PERSON> Kociemba </PERSON>, who claimed the birth control device had left her infertile. The three jurors, whose names were withheld at their request, also indicated they did not believe the plaintiff proved her claim that the device caused her injuries. The judgment represented the first jury award of punitive damages against <PERSON> Searle </PERSON> in a Copper 7 case. The pharmaceutical company has won 15 of 19 Copper 7 damage cases that have gone before a jury. <ORGANIZATION> Monsanto </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schannon </PERSON> said <PERSON> Searle </PERSON> attorneys would introduce motions to vacate the award. <PERSON> Renner </PERSON> will hear the motions Dec. 1 in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paul </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Schannon </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Renner </PERSON> can let the verdict stand, reduce the award or order a new trial, <PERSON> Schannon </PERSON> said. The letter from the three jurors claimed that `` continual verbal harassment and intimidation'' by the jury foreman during deliberations prevented them from expressing their opinion about the trial evidence. `` Our failure to understand the purpose and-or power of the jury foreman facilitated our inability to express individual opinions,'' the letter read. The three jurors also stated that a desire to inform the court of a 4-4 split among jury was prevented by `` a convenient interpretation of the jury and judge's instructions.'' `` Any opinions which conflicted with the foreman's -LRB- plaintiff's -RRB- views were met with disdain and contempt and resulted in additional verbal and-or physical harassment,'' the letter said. `` When the obvious difference of opinion became apparent, discussions and negotiations ceased. `` While believing that <PERSON> Searle </PERSON> may have been negligent in advertising, we individually assessed that <PERSON> Esther </PERSON> <PERSON> Kociemba </PERSON> never proved that the CU-7 caused her injuries ...'' the letter read. `` Summarily, we individually and collectively feel ashamed and embarrassed to be associated with a verdict against our true opinions,'' the three wrote. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Duesenberg </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Monsanto </ORGANIZATION>'s general counsel, said the jurors wrote the letter on their own initiative and neither <ORGANIZATION> Monsanto </ORGANIZATION> nor <PERSON> Searle </PERSON> saw the letter until it was received by <PERSON> Renner </PERSON>. `` This is an important letter for our shareholders for two reasons: first, the plaintiff's attorneys failed to convince the full jury that the Cu-7 cause the plaintiff's injuries, and second, this case should not be viewed as a watershed,'' <PERSON> Duesenberg </PERSON> said. In <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, Mrs. <PERSON> Kociemba </PERSON>'s attorney issued a statement labeling the letter legally irrelevant, and accusing <PERSON> Searle </PERSON> lawyers of having met with the three jurors. `` This is simploy a desperate and futile attempt by <PERSON> Searle </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Monsanto </ORGANIZATION> to achieve a result they could n't achieve in court,'' stated lawyer <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Ciresi </PERSON>. `` This is nothing more than post-verdict jury tampering.''
